obj_root_law_sections_1:
  sectionId (90767)
  sectionNo (1)
  orderNo 1
  title `Short title, application and commencement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_1_content
  footnotes `1. 1st July, 2024, vide notification No. S.O. 849(E), dated, 23rd day of February, 2024, see Gazette of India, Extraordinary, Part II, sec. 3(ii).`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90767&sectionno=1&orderno=1&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_1_content:
  string
  line `(1) This Act may be called the Bharatiya Sakshya`
  line `Adhiniyam, 2023.`
  line
  line `(2) It applies to all judicial proceedings in or before any Court, including Courts-martial, but not to`
  line `affidavits presented to any Court or officer, nor to proceedings before an arbitrator.`
  line
  line `(3) It shall come into force on such date^1`
  line `as the Central Government may, by notification in the`
  line `Official Gazette, appoint.`
obj_root_law_sections_2:
  sectionId (90768)
  sectionNo (2)
  orderNo 2
  title Definitions.
  content obj_root_law_sections_2_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_2_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90768&sectionno=2&orderno=2&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_2_content:
  string
  line `(1) In this Adhiniyam, unless the context otherwise requires,--`
  line
  line `(a) "Court" includes all Judges and Magistrates, and all persons, except arbitrators, legally authorised to take evidence;`
  line
  line `(b) "conclusive proof" means when one fact is declared by this Adhiniyam to be conclusive proof of another, the Court shall, on proof of the one fact, regard the other as proved, and shall not allow evidence to be given for the purpose of disproving it;`
  line
  line `(c) "disproved" in relation to a fact, means when, after considering the matters before it, the Court either believes that it does not exist, or considers its non-existence so probable that a prudent man ought, under the circumstances of the particular case, to act upon the supposition that it does not exist;`
  line
  line `(d) "document" means any matter expressed or described or otherwise recorded upon any substance by means of letters, figures or marks or any other means or by more than one of those means, intended to be used, or which may be used, for the purpose of recording that matter and includes electronic and digital records.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(i) A writing is a document.`
  line
  line `(ii) Words printed, lithographed or photographed are documents.`
  line
  line `(iii) A map or plan is a document.`
  line
  line `(iv) An inscription on a metal plate or stone is a document.`
  line
  line `(v) A caricature is a document.`
  line
  line `(vi) An electronic record on emails, server logs, documents on computers, laptop or smartphone, messages, websites, locational evidence and voice mail messages stored on digital devices are documents;`
  line
  line `(e) "evidence" means and includes--`
  line
  line `(i) all statements including statements given electronically which the Court permits or requires to be made before it by witnesses in relation to matters of fact under inquiry and such statements are called oral evidence;`
  line
  line `(ii) all documents including electronic or digital records produced for the inspection of the Court and such documents are called documentary evidence;`
  line
  line `(f) "fact" means and includes--`
  line
  line `(i) any thing, state of things, or relation of things, capable of being perceived by the senses;`
  line
  line `(ii) any mental condition of which any person is conscious.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(i) That there are certain objects arranged in a certain order in a certain place, is a fact.`
  line
  line `(ii) That a person heard or saw something, is a fact`
  line
  line `(iii) That a person said certain words, is a fact`
  line
  line `(iv) That a person holds a certain opinion, has a certain intention, acts in good faith, or fraudulently, or uses a particular word in a particular sense, or is or was at a specified time conscious of a particular sensation, is a fact;`
  line
  line `(g) "facts in issue" means and includes any fact from which, either by itself or in connection with other facts, the existence, non-existence, nature or extent of any right, liability or disability, asserted or denied in any suit or proceeding, necessarily follows.`
  line
  line `Explanation. --Whenever, under the provisions of the law for the time being in force relating to Civil Procedure, any Court records an issue of fact, the fact to be asserted or denied in the answer to such issue is a fact in issue.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `A is accused of the murder of B. At his trial, the following facts may be in issue:--`
  line
  line `(i) That A caused B's death`
  line
  line `(ii) That A intended to cause B's death`
  line
  line `(iii) That A had received grave and sudden provocation from B.`
  line
  line `(iv) That A, at the time of doing the act which caused Bs death, was, by reason of unsoundness of mind, incapable of knowing its nature;`
  line
  line `(h) "may presume".--Whenever it is provided by this Adhiniyam that the Court may presume a fact, it may either regard such fact as proved, unless and until it is disproved or may call for proof of it;`
  line
  line `(i) "not proved".--A fact is said to be not proved when it is neither proved nor disproved;`
  line
  line `(j) "proved".--A fact is said to be proved when, after considering the matters before it, the Court either believes it to exist, or considers its existence so probable that a prudent man ought, under the circumstances of the particular case, to act upon the supposition that it exists;`
  line
  line `(k) "relevant".--A fact is said to be relevant to another when it is connected with the other in any of the ways referred to in the provisions of this Adhiniyam relating to the relevancy of facts;`
  line
  line `(l) "shall presume".--Whenever it is directed by this Adhiniyam that the Court shall presume a fact, it shall regard such fact as proved, unless and until it is disproved.`
  line
  line `(2) Words and expressions used herein and not defined but defined in the Information Technology Act, 2000 (21 of 2000), the Bharatiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita, 2023 and the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023 shall have the same meanings as assigned to them in the said Act and Sanhitas.`
obj_root_law_sections_2_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_3:
  sectionId (90769)
  sectionNo (3)
  orderNo 3
  title `Evidence may be given of facts in issue and relevant facts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_3_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90769&sectionno=3&orderno=3&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_3_content:
  string
  line `Evidence may be given in any suit`
  line `or proceeding of the existence or non-existence of every fact in issue and of such other facts as are`
  line `hereinafter declared to be relevant, and of no others.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--This section shall not enable any person to give evidence of a fact which he is disentitled to prove by any provision of the law for the time being in force relating to civil procedure.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A is tried for the murder of B by beating him with a club with the intention of causing his death.`
  line
  line `At A's trial the following facts are in issue:--`
  line
  line `A's beating B with the club;`
  line
  line `A's causing B's death by such beating;`
  line
  line `A's intention to cause B's death.`
  line
  line `(b) A suitor does not bring with him, and have in readiness for production at the first hearing of the case, a bond on which he relies. This section does not enable him to produce the bond or prove its contents at a subsequent stage of the proceedings, otherwise than in accordance with the conditions prescribed by the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 (5 of 1908).`
obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_4:
  sectionId (90770)
  sectionNo (4)
  orderNo 4
  title `Relevancy of facts forming part of same transaction.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_4_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90770&sectionno=4&orderno=4&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_4_content:
  string
  line `Facts which, though not in issue, are so`
  line `connected with a fact in issue or a relevant fact as to form part of the same transaction, are relevant, whether they occurred at the same time and place or at different times and places.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A is accused of the murder of B by beating him. Whatever was said or done by A or B or the bystanders at the beating, or so shortly before or after it as to form part of the transaction, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(b) A is accused of waging war against the Government of India by taking part in an armed insurrection in which property is destroyed, troops are attacked and jails are broken open. The occurrence of these facts is relevant, as forming part of the general transaction, though A may not have been present at all of them.`
  line
  line `(c) A sues B for a libel contained in a letter forming part of a correspondence. Letters between the parties relating to the subject out of which the libel arose, and forming part of the correspondence in which it is contained, are relevant facts, though they do not contain the libel itself.`
  line
  line `(d) The question is, whether certain goods ordered from B were delivered to A. The goods were delivered to several intermediate persons successively. Each delivery is a relevant fact.`
obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_5:
  sectionId (90771)
  sectionNo (5)
  orderNo 5
  title `Facts which are occasion, cause or effect of facts in issue or relevant facts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_5_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90771&sectionno=5&orderno=5&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_5_content:
  string
  line `Facts which are the occasion, cause or effect, immediate or otherwise, of relevant facts, or facts in issue, or which constitute the state of things under which they happened, or which afforded an opportunity for their occurrence or transaction, are relevant.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) The question is, whether A robbed B. The facts that, shortly before the robbery, B went to a fair with money in his possession, and that he showed it, or mentioned the fact that he had it, to third persons, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(b) The question is, whether A murdered B. Marks on the ground, produced by a struggle at or near`
  line `the place where the murder was committed, are relevant facts.`
  line
  line `(c) The question is, whether A poisoned B. The state of B's health before the symptoms ascribed to`
  line `poison, and habits of B, known to A, which afforded an opportunity for the administration of poison, are`
  line `relevant facts.`
obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_6:
  sectionId (90772)
  sectionNo (6)
  orderNo 6
  title `Motive, preparation and previous or subsequent conduct.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_6_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90772&sectionno=6&orderno=6&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line `(1) Any fact is relevant which`
  line `shows or constitutes a motive or preparation for any fact in issue or relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(2) The conduct of any party, or of any agent to any party, to any suit or proceeding, in reference to such suit or proceeding, or in reference to any fact in issue therein or relevant thereto, and the conduct of any person, an offence against whom is the subject of any proceeding, is relevant, if such conduct influences or is influenced by any fact in issue or relevant fact, and whether it was previous or subsequent thereto.`
  line
  line `Explanation 1.--The word "conduct" in this section does not include statements, unless those statements accompany and explain acts other than statements; but this explanation is not to affect the relevancy of statements under any other section of this Adhiniyam.`
  line
  line `Explanation 2.--When the conduct of any person is relevant, any statement made to him or in his presence and hearing, which affects such conduct, is relevant.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A is tried for the murder of B. The facts that A murdered C, that B knew that A had murdered C, and that B had tried to extort money from A by threatening to make his knowledge public, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(b) A sues B upon a bond for the payment of money. B denies the making of the bond. The fact that, at the time when the bond was alleged to be made, B required money for a particular purpose, is relevant.`
  line
  line `(c) A is tried for the murder of B by poison. The fact that, before the death of B, A procured poison similar to that which was administered to B, is relevant.`
  line
  line `(d) The question is, whether a certain document is the will of A. The facts that, not long before, the date of the alleged will, A made inquiry into matters to which the provisions of the alleged will relate; that he consulted advocates in reference to making the will, and that he caused drafts of other wills to be prepared, of which he did not approve, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(e) A is accused of a crime. The facts that, either before, or at the time of, or after the alleged crime, A provided evidence which would tend to give to the facts of the case an appearance favourable to himself, or that he destroyed or concealed evidence, or prevented the presence or procured the absence of persons who might have been witnesses, or suborned persons to give false evidence respecting it, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(f) The question is, whether A robbed B. The facts that, after B was robbed, C said in A's presence-- "the police are coming to look for the person who robbed B", and that immediately afterwards A ran away, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(g) The question is, whether A owes B ten thousand rupees. The facts that A asked C to lend him money, and that D said to C in A's presence and hearing--"I advise you not to trust A, for he owes B ten thousand rupees", and that A went away without making any answer, are relevant facts.`
  line
  line `(h) The question is, whether A committed a crime. The fact that A absconded, after receiving a letter, warning A that inquiry was being made for the criminal, and the contents of the letter, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(i) A is accused of a crime. The facts that, after the commission of the alleged crime, A absconded, or was in possession of property or the proceeds of property acquired by the crime, or attempted to conceal things which were or might have been used in committing it, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(j) The question is, whether A was raped. The fact that, shortly after the alleged rape, A made a complaint relating to the crime, the circumstances under which, and the terms in which, the complaint was made, are relevant. The fact that, without making a complaint, A said that A had been raped is not relevant as conduct under this section, though it may be relevant as a dying declaration under clause (a) of section 26, or as corroborative evidence under section 160.`
  line
  line `(k) The question is, whether A was robbed. The fact that, soon after the alleged robbery, A made a complaint relating to the offence, the circumstances under which, and the terms in which, the complaint was made, are relevant. The fact that A said he had been robbed, without making any complaint, is not relevant, as conduct under this section, though it may be relevant as a dying declaration under clause (a) of section 26, or as corroborative evidence under section 160.`
obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_7:
  sectionId (90773)
  sectionNo (7)
  orderNo 7
  title `Facts necessary to explain or introduce fact in issue or relevant facts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_7_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90773&sectionno=7&orderno=7&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_7_content:
  string
  line `Facts necessary to explain or introduce a fact in issue or relevant fact, or which support or rebut an inference suggested by a fact in issue or a relevant fact, or which establish the identity of anything, or person whose identity, is relevant, or fix the time or place at which any fact in issue or relevant fact happened, or which show the relation of parties by whom any such fact was transacted, are relevant in so far as they are necessary for`
  line `that purpose.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) The question is, whether a given document is the will of A. The state of A's property and of his family at the date of the alleged will may be relevant facts.`
  line
  line `(b) A sues B for a libel imputing disgraceful conduct to A; B affirms that the matter alleged to be`
  line `libellous is true. The position and relations of the parties at the time when the libel was published may be`
  line `relevant facts as introductory to the facts in issue. The particulars of a dispute between A and B about a`
  line `matter unconnected with the alleged libel are irrelevant, though the fact that there was a dispute may be`
  line `relevant if it affected the relations between A and B.`
  line
  line `(c) A is accused of a crime. The fact that, soon after the commission of the crime, A absconded from`
  line `his house, is relevant under section 6, as conduct subsequent to and affected by facts in issue. The fact`
  line `that, at the time when he left home, A had sudden and urgent business at the place to which he went, is`
  line `relevant, as tending to explain the fact that he left home suddenly. The details of the business on which he`
  line `left are not relevant, except in so far as they are necessary to show that the business was sudden and`
  line urgent
  line
  line `(d) A sues B for inducing C to break a contract of service made by him with A. C, on leaving A's`
  line `service, says to A--"I am leaving you because B has made me a better offer". This statement is a relevant fact as explanatory of C's conduct, which is relevant as a fact in issue.`
  line
  line `(e) A, accused of theft, is seen to give the stolen property to B, who is seen to give it to A's wife. B says as he delivers it--"A says you are to hide this". B's statement is relevant as explanatory of a fact which is part of the transaction.`
  line
  line `(f) A is tried for a riot and is proved to have marched at the head of a mob. The cries of the mob are relevant as explanatory of the nature of the transaction.`
obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_8:
  sectionId (90774)
  sectionNo (8)
  orderNo 8
  title `Things said or done by conspirator in reference to common design.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_8_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90774&sectionno=8&orderno=8&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_8_content:
  string
  line `Where there is`
  line `reasonable ground to believe that two or more persons have conspired together to commit an offence or`
  line `an actionable wrong, anything said, done or written by any one of such persons in reference to their`
  line `common intention, after the time when such intention was first entertained by any one of them, is a`
  line `relevant fact as against each of the persons believed to be so conspiring, as well for the purpose of`
  line `proving the existence of the conspiracy as for the purpose of showing that any such person was a party to`
  line it.
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `Reasonable ground exists for believing that A has joined in a conspiracy to wage war against the`
  line State.
  line
  line `The facts that B procured arms in Europe for the purpose of the conspiracy, C collected money in`
  line `Kolkata for a like object, D persuaded persons to join the conspiracy in Mumbai, E published writings`
  line `advocating the object in view at Agra, and F transmitted from Delhi to G at Singapore the money which`
  line `C had collected at Kolkata, and the contents of a letter written by H giving an account of the conspiracy,`
  line `are each relevant, both to prove the existence of the conspiracy, and to prove A's complicity in it,`
  line `although he may have been ignorant of all of them, and although the persons by whom they were done`
  line `were strangers to him, and although they may have taken place before he joined the conspiracy or after he`
  line `left it.`
obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_9:
  sectionId (90775)
  sectionNo (9)
  orderNo 9
  title `When facts not otherwise relevant become relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_9_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90775&sectionno=9&orderno=9&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_9_content:
  string
  line `Facts not otherwise relevant are`
  line relevant--
  line
  line `(1) if they are inconsistent with any fact in issue or relevant fact;`
  line
  line `(2) if by themselves or in connection with other facts they make the existence or non-existence of`
  line `any fact in issue or relevant fact highly probable or improbable.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) The question is, whether A committed a crime at Chennai on a certain day. The fact that, on that`
  line `day, A was at Ladakh is relevant. The fact that, near the time when the crime was committed, A was at a`
  line `distance from the place where it was committed, which would render it highly improbable, though not`
  line `impossible, that he committed it, is relevant.`
  line
  line `(b) The question is, whether A committed a crime. The circumstances are such that the crime must`
  line `have been committed either by A, B, C or D. Every fact which shows that the crime could have been`
  line `committed by no one else, and that it was not committed by either B, C or D, is relevant.`
obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_10:
  sectionId (90776)
  sectionNo (10)
  orderNo 10
  title `Facts tending to enable Court to determine amount are relevant in suits for damages.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_10_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90776&sectionno=10&orderno=10&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_10_content:
  string
  line In
  line `suits in which damages are claimed, any fact which will enable the Court to determine the amount of`
  line `damages which ought to be awarded, is relevant`
obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_11:
  sectionId (90777)
  sectionNo (11)
  orderNo 11
  title `Facts relevant when right or custom is in question.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_11_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90777&sectionno=11&orderno=11&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_11_content:
  string
  line `Where the question is as to the existence`
  line `of any right or custom, the following facts are relevant--`
  line
  line `(a) any transaction by which the right or custom in question was created, claimed, modified,`
  line `recognised, asserted or denied, or which was inconsistent with its existence;`
  line
  line `(b) particular instances in which the right or custom was claimed, recognised or exercised, or in`
  line `which its exercise was disputed, asserted or departed from.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `The question is, whether A has a right to a fishery. A deed conferring the fishery on A's ancestors, a`
  line `mortgage of the fishery by A's father, a subsequent grant of the fishery by A's father, irreconcilable with`
  line `the mortgage, particular instances in which A's father exercised the right, or in which the exercise of the`
  line `right was stopped by A's neighbours, are relevant facts.`
obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_12:
  sectionId (90778)
  sectionNo (12)
  orderNo 12
  title `Facts showing existence of state of mind, or of body or bodily feeling.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_12_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90778&sectionno=12&orderno=12&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_12_content:
  string
  line `Facts showing the`
  line `existence of any state of mind, such as intention, knowledge, good faith, negligence, rashness, ill-will or`
  line `goodwill towards any particular person, or showing the existence of any state of body or bodily feeling,`
  line `are relevant, when the existence of any such state of mind or body or bodily feeling is in issue or relevant.`
  line
  line `Explanation 1.--A fact relevant as showing the existence of a relevant state of mind must show that the state of mind exists, not generally, but in reference to the particular matter in question.`
  line
  line `Explanation 2.--But where, upon the trial of a person accused of an offence, the previous commission by the accused of an offence is relevant within the meaning of this section, the previous conviction of such person shall also be a relevant fact.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A is accused of receiving stolen goods knowing them to be stolen. It is proved that he was in possession of a particular stolen article. The fact that, at the same time, he was in possession of many other stolen articles is relevant, as tending to show that he knew each and all of the articles of which he was in possession to be stolen.`
  line
  line `(b) A is accused of fraudulently delivering to another person a counterfeit currency which, at the time when he delivered it, he knew to be counterfeit. The fact that, at the time of its delivery, A was possessed of a number of other pieces of counterfeit currency is relevant. The fact that A had been previously convicted of delivering to another person as genuine a counterfeit currency knowing it to be counterfeit is`
  line relevant.
  line
  line `(c) A sues B for damage done by a dog of B's, which B knew to be ferocious. The fact that the dog had previously bitten X, Y and Z, and that they had made complaints to B, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(d) The question is, whether A, the acceptor of a bill of exchange, knew that the name of the payee`
  line `was fictitious. The fact that A had accepted other bills drawn in the same manner before they could have`
  line `been transmitted to him by the payee if the payee had been a real person, is relevant, as showing that A`
  line `knew that the payee was a fictitious person.`
  line
  line `(e) A is accused of defaming B by publishing an imputation intended to harm the reputation of B. The fact of previous publications by A respecting B, showing ill-will on the part of A towards B is relevant, as proving A's intention to harm B's reputation by the particular publication in question. The facts that there was no previous quarrel between A and B, and that A repeated the matter complained of as he heard it, are relevant, as showing that A did not intend to harm the reputation of B.`
  line
  line `(f) A is sued by B for fraudulently representing to B that C was solvent, whereby B, being induced to`
  line `trust C, who was insolvent, suffered loss. The fact that, at the time when A represented C to be solvent, C`
  line `was supposed to be solvent by his neighbours and by persons dealing with him, is relevant, as showing`
  line `that A made the representation in good faith.`
  line
  line `(g) A is sued by B for the price of work done by B, upon a house of which A is owner, by the order`
  line `of C, a contractor. A's defence is that B's contract was with C. The fact that A paid C for the work in`
  line `question is relevant, as proving that A did, in good faith, make over to C the management of the work in`
  line `question, so that C was in a position to contract with B on C's own account, and not as agent for A.`
  line
  line `(h) A is accused of the dishonest misappropriation of property which he had found, and the question`
  line `is whether, when he appropriated it, he believed in good faith that the real owner could not be found. The`
  line `fact that public notice of the loss of the property had been given in the place where A was, is relevant, as`
  line `showing that A did not in good faith believe that the real owner of the property could not be found. The`
  line `fact that A knew, or had reason to believe, that the notice was given fraudulently by C, who had heard of`
  line `the loss of the property and wished to set up a false claim to it, is relevant, as showing that the fact that A`
  line `knew of the notice did not disprove A's good faith.`
  line
  line `(i) A is charged with shooting at B with intent to kill him. In order to show A's intent, the fact of A's`
  line `having previously shot at B may be proved.`
  line
  line `(j) A is charged with sending threatening letters to B. Threatening letters previously sent by A to B`
  line `may be proved, as showing the intention of the letters.`
  line
  line `(k) The question is, whether A has been guilty of cruelty towards B, his wife. Expressions of their`
  line `feeling towards each other shortly before or after the alleged cruelty are relevant facts.`
  line
  line `(l) The question is, whether A's death was caused by poison. Statements made by A during his illness`
  line `as to his symptoms are relevant facts.`
  line
  line `(m) The question is, what was the state of A's health at the time when an assurance on his life was`
  line `effected. Statements made by A as to the state of his health at or near the time in question are relevant`
  line facts.
  line
  line `(n) A sues B for negligence in providing him with a car for hire not reasonably fit for use, whereby A`
  line `was injured. The fact that B's attention was drawn on other occasions to the defect of that particular car is`
  line `relevant. The fact that B was habitually negligent about the cars which he let to hire is irrelevant.`
  line
  line `(o) A is tried for the murder of B by intentionally shooting him dead. The fact that A on other`
  line `occasions shot at B is relevant as showing his intention to shoot B. The fact that A was in the habit of`
  line `shooting at people with intent to murder them is irrelevant.`
  line
  line `(p) A is tried for a crime. The fact that he said something indicating an intention to commit that`
  line `particular crime is relevant. The fact that he said something indicating a general disposition to commit`
  line `crimes of that class is irrelevant.`
obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_13:
  sectionId (90779)
  sectionNo (13)
  orderNo 13
  title `Facts bearing on question whether act was accidental or intentional.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_13_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90779&sectionno=13&orderno=13&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_13_content:
  string
  line `When there is a`
  line `question whether an act was accidental or intentional, or done with a particular knowledge or intention,`
  line `the fact that such act formed part of a series of similar occurrences, in each of which the person doing the`
  line `act was concerned, is relevant.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A is accused of burning down his house in order to obtain money for which it is insured. The facts`
  line `that A lived in several houses successively each of which he insured, in each of which a fire occurred,`
  line `and after each of which fires A received payment from a different insurance company, are relevant, as`
  line `tending to show that the fires were not accidental.`
  line
  line `(b) A is employed to receive money from the debtors of B. It is A's duty to make entries in a book`
  line `showing the amounts received by him. He makes an entry showing that on a particular occasion he`
  line `received less than he really did receive. The question is, whether this false entry was accidental or`
  line `intentional. The facts that other entries made by A in the same book are false, and that the false entry is in`
  line `each case in favour of A, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(c) A is accused of fraudulently delivering to B a counterfeit currency. The question is, whether the`
  line `delivery of the currency was accidental. The facts that, soon before or soon after the delivery to B, A`
  line `delivered counterfeit currency to C, D and E are relevant, as showing that the delivery to B was not`
  line accidental.
obj_root_law_sections_13_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_14:
  sectionId (90780)
  sectionNo (14)
  orderNo 14
  title `Existence of course of business when relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_14_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90780&sectionno=14&orderno=14&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_14_content:
  string
  line `When there is a question whether a particular`
  line `act was done, the existence of any course of business, according to which it naturally would have been`
  line `done, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) The question is, whether a particular letter was dispatched. The facts that it was the ordinary`
  line `course of business for all letters put in a certain place to be carried to the post, and that particular letter`
  line `was put in that place are relevant.`
  line
  line `(b) The question is, whether a particular letter reached A. The facts that it was posted in due course,`
  line `and was not returned through the Return Letter Office, are relevant.`
obj_root_law_sections_14_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_15:
  sectionId (90781)
  sectionNo (15)
  orderNo 15
  title `Admission defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_15_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90781&sectionno=15&orderno=15&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_15_content:
  string
  line `An admission is a statement, oral or documentary or contained in`
  line `electronic form, which suggests any inference as to any fact in issue or relevant fact, and which is made`
  line `by any of the persons, and under the circumstances, hereinafter mentioned.`
obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_16:
  sectionId (90782)
  sectionNo (16)
  orderNo 16
  title `Admission by party to proceeding or his agent.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_16_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90782&sectionno=16&orderno=16&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_16_content:
  string
  line `(1) Statements made by a party to the`
  line `proceeding, or by an agent to any such party, whom the Court regards, under the circumstances of the`
  line `case, as expressly or impliedly authorised by him to make them, are admissions.`
  line
  line `(2) Statements made by--`
  line
  line `(i) parties to suits suing or sued in a representative character, are not admissions, unless they were made while the party making them held that character; or`
  line
  line `(ii) (a) persons who have any proprietary or pecuniary interest in the subject matter of the proceeding, and who make the statement in their character of persons so interested; or`
  line
  line `(b) persons from whom the parties to the suit have derived their interest in the subject matter of the suit,`
  line
  line `are admissions, if they are made during the continuance of the interest of the persons making the`
  line statements
obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_17:
  sectionId (90783)
  sectionNo (17)
  orderNo 17
  title `Admissions by persons whose position must be proved as against party to suit.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_17_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90783&sectionno=17&orderno=17&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_17_content:
  string
  line `Statements made by persons whose position or liability, it is necessary to prove as against any party to the suit, are admissions, if such statements would be relevant as against such persons in relation to such position or liability in a suit brought by or against them, and if they are made whilst the person making them occupies such position or is subject to such liability`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A undertakes to collect rents for B. B sues A for not collecting rent due from C to B. A denies that`
  line `rent was due from C to B. A statement by C that he owed B rent is an admission, and is a relevant fact as`
  line `against A, if A denies that C did owe rent to B.`
obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_18:
  sectionId (90784)
  sectionNo (18)
  orderNo 18
  title `Admissions by persons expressly referred to by party to suit.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_18_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90784&sectionno=18&orderno=18&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_18_content:
  string
  line `Statements made by persons to`
  line `whom a party to the suit has expressly referred for information in reference to a matter in dispute are`
  line admissions.
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `The question is, whether a horse sold by A to B is sound.`
  line
  line `A says to B-- "Go and ask C, C knows all about it". C's statement is an admission.`
obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_19:
  sectionId (90785)
  sectionNo (19)
  orderNo 19
  title `Proof of admissions against persons making them, and by or on their behalf.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_19_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90785&sectionno=19&orderno=19&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_19_content:
  string
  line `Admissions are relevant and may be proved as against the person who makes them, or his representative in interest;`
  line `but they cannot be proved by or on behalf of the person who makes them or by his representative in`
  line `interest, except in the following cases, namely:--`
  line
  line `(1) an admission may be proved by or on behalf of the person making it, when it is of such a`
  line `nature that, if the person making it were dead, it would be relevant as between third persons under`
  line `section 26;`
  line
  line `(2) an admission may be proved by or on behalf of the person making it, when it consists of a`
  line `statement of the existence of any state of mind or body, relevant or in issue, made at or about the time`
  line `when such state of mind or body existed, and is accompanied by conduct rendering its falsehood`
  line improbable;
  line
  line `(3) an admission may be proved by or on behalf of the person making it, if it is relevant`
  line `otherwise than as an admission.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) The question between A and B is, whether a certain deed is or is not forged. A affirms that it is`
  line `genuine, B that it is forged. A may prove a statement by B that the deed is genuine, and B may prove a`
  line `statement by A that deed is forged; but A cannot prove a statement by himself that the deed is genuine,`
  line `nor can B prove a statement by himself that the deed is forged.`
  line
  line `(b) A, the captain of a ship, is tried for casting her away. Evidence is given to show that the ship was`
  line `taken out of her proper course. A produces a book kept by him in the ordinary course of his business`
  line `showing observations alleged to have been taken by him from day to day, and indicating that the ship was`
  line `not taken out of her proper course. A may prove these statements, because they would be admissible`
  line `between third parties, if he were dead, under clause (b) of section 26.`
  line
  line `(c) A is accused of a crime committed by him at Kolkata. He produces a letter written by himself and`
  line `dated at Chennai on that day, and bearing the Chennai post-mark of that day. The statement in the date of`
  line `the letter is admissible, because, if A were dead, it would be admissible under clause (b) of section 26.`
  line
  line `(d) A is accused of receiving stolen goods knowing them to be stolen. He offers to prove that he`
  line `refused to sell them below their value. A may prove these statements, though they are admissions,`
  line `because they are explanatory of conduct influenced by facts in issue.`
  line
  line `(e) A is accused of fraudulently having in his possession counterfeit currency which he knew to be`
  line `counterfeit. He offers to prove that he asked a skilful person to examine the currency as he doubted`
  line `whether it was counterfeit or not, and that person did examine it and told him it was genuine. A may`
  line `prove these facts.`
obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_20:
  sectionId (90786)
  sectionNo (20)
  orderNo 20
  title `When oral admissions as to contents of documents are relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_20_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90786&sectionno=20&orderno=20&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_20_content:
  string
  line `Oral admissions as to the`
  line `contents of a document are not relevant, unless and until the party proposing to prove them shows that he`
  line `is entitled to give secondary evidence of the contents of such document under the rules hereinafter`
  line `contained, or unless the genuineness of a document produced is in question`
obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_21:
  sectionId (90787)
  sectionNo (21)
  orderNo 21
  title `Admissions in civil cases when relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_21_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90787&sectionno=21&orderno=21&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_21_content:
  string
  line `In civil cases no admission is relevant, if it is made`
  line `either upon an express condition that evidence of it is not to be given, or under circumstances from which`
  line `the Court can infer that the parties agreed together that evidence of it should not be given.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--Nothing in this section shall be taken to exempt any advocate from giving evidence of`
  line `any matter of which he may be compelled to give evidence under sub-sections (1) and (2) of section 132.`
obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_22:
  sectionId (90938)
  sectionNo (22)
  orderNo 22
  title `Confession caused by inducement, threat, coercion or promise, when irrelevant in criminal proceeding.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_22_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_22_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90938&sectionno=22&orderno=22&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_22_content:
  string
  line `A confession made by an accused person is irrelevant in a criminal proceeding, if the`
  line `making of the confession appears to the Court to have been caused by any inducement, threat, coercion or`
  line `promise having reference to the charge against the accused person, proceeding from a person in authority`
  line `and sufficient, in the opinion of the Court, to give the accused person grounds which would appear to him`
  line `reasonable for supposing that by making it he would gain any advantage or avoid any evil of a temporal`
  line `nature in reference to the proceedings against him:`
  line
  line `Provided that if the confession is made after the impression caused by any such inducement, threat,`
  line `coercion or promise has, in the opinion of the Court, been fully removed, it is relevant:`
  line
  line `Provided further that if such a confession is otherwise relevant, it does not become irrelevant merely`
  line `because it was made under a promise of secrecy, or in consequence of a deception practised on the`
  line `accused person for the purpose of obtaining it, or when he was drunk, or because it was made in answer`
  line `to questions which he need not have answered, whatever may have been the form of those questions, or`
  line `because he was not warned that he was not bound to make such confession, and that evidence of it might`
  line `be given against him.`
obj_root_law_sections_22_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_23:
  sectionId (90789)
  sectionNo (23)
  orderNo 23
  title `Confession to police officer.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_23_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_23_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90789&sectionno=23&orderno=23&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_23_content:
  string
  line `(1) No confession made to a police officer shall be proved as`
  line `against a person accused of any offence`
  line
  line `(2) No confession made by any person while he is in the custody of a police officer, unless it is made`
  line `in the immediate presence of a Magistrate shall be proved against him:`
  line
  line `Provided that when any fact is deposed to as discovered in consequence of information received from`
  line `a person accused of any offence, in the custody of a police officer, so much of such information, whether`
  line `it amounts to a confession or not, as relates distinctly to the fact discovered, may be proved.`
obj_root_law_sections_23_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_24:
  sectionId (90939)
  sectionNo (24)
  orderNo 24
  title `Consideration of proved confession affecting person making it and others jointly under trial for same offence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_24_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_24_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90939&sectionno=24&orderno=24&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_24_content:
  string
  line `When more persons than one are being tried jointly for the same offence, and a`
  line `confession made by one of such persons affecting himself and some other of such persons is proved, the`
  line `Court may take into consideration such confession as against such other person as well as against the`
  line `person who makes such confession.`
  line
  line `Explanation I.--"Offence", as used in this section, includes the abetment of, or attempt to commit,`
  line `the offence.`
  line
  line `Explanation II.--A trial of more persons than one held in the absence of the accused who has`
  line `absconded or who fails to comply with a proclamation issued under section 84 of the Bharatiya Nagarik`
  line `Suraksha Sanhita, 2023 shall be deemed to be a joint trial for the purpose of this section`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A and B are jointly tried for the murder of C. It is proved that A said--"B and I murdered C". The`
  line `Court may consider the effect of this confession as against B.`
  line
  line `(b) A is on his trial for the murder of C. There is evidence to show that C was murdered by A and B,`
  line `and that B said-- "A and I murdered C". This statement may not be taken into consideration by the Court against A, as B is not being jointly tried.`
obj_root_law_sections_24_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_25:
  sectionId (90791)
  sectionNo (25)
  orderNo 25
  title `Admissions not conclusive proof, but may estop.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_25_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_25_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90791&sectionno=25&orderno=25&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_25_content:
  string
  line `Admissions are not conclusive proof of the`
  line `matters admitted but they may operate as estoppels under the provisions hereinafter contained.`
obj_root_law_sections_25_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_26:
  sectionId (90940)
  sectionNo (26)
  orderNo 26
  title `Cases in which statement of relevant fact by person who is dead or cannot be found, etc., is relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_26_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_26_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90940&sectionno=26&orderno=26&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_26_content:
  string
  line `Statements, written or verbal, of relevant facts made by a person who is dead, or who cannot be found, or who has become incapable of giving evidence, or whose attendance cannot be procured without an amount of delay or expense which under the circumstances of the case appears to the Court unreasonable, are themselves relevant facts in the following cases, namely:--`
  line
  line `(a) when the statement is made by a person as to the cause of his death, or as to any of the circumstances of the transaction which resulted in his death, in cases in which the cause of that person's death comes into question. Such statements are relevant whether the person who made them was or was not, at the time when they were made, under expectation of death, and whatever may be the nature of the proceeding in which the cause of his death comes into question;`
  line
  line `(b) when the statement was made by such person in the ordinary course of business, and in particular when it consists of any entry or memorandum made by him in books kept in the ordinary course of business, or in the discharge of professional duty; or of an acknowledgement written or signed by him of the receipt of money, goods, securities or property of any kind; or of a document used in commerce written or signed by him; or of the date of a letter or other document usually dated, written or signed by him;`
  line
  line `(c) when the statement is against the pecuniary or proprietary interest of the person making it, or when, if true, it would expose him or would have exposed him to a criminal prosecution or to a suit for damages;`
  line
  line `(d) when the statement gives the opinion of any such person, as to the existence of any public right or custom or matter of public or general interest, of the existence of which, if it existed, he would have been likely to be aware, and when such statement was made before any controversy as to such right, custom or matter had arisen;`
  line
  line `(e) when the statement relates to the existence of any relationship by blood, marriage or adoption between persons as to whose relationship by blood, marriage or adoption the person making the statement had special means of knowledge, and when the statement was made before the question in dispute was raised;`
  line
  line `(f) when the statement relates to the existence of any relationship by blood, marriage or adoption between persons deceased, and is made in any will or deed relating to the affairs of the family to which any such deceased person belonged, or in any family pedigree, or upon any tombstone, family portrait or other thing on which such statements are usually made, and when such statement was made before the question in dispute was raised;`
  line
  line `(g) when the statement is contained in any deed, will or other document which relates to any such transaction as is specified in clause (a) of section 11;`
  line
  line `(h) when the statement was made by a number of persons, and expressed feelings or impressions on their part relevant to the matter in question.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) The question is, whether A was murdered by B; or A dies of injuries received in a transaction in the course of which she was raped. The question is whether she was raped by B; or the question is, whether A was killed by B under such circumstances that a suit would lie against B by A's widow. Statements made by A as to the cause of his or her death, referring respectively to the murder, the rape and the actionable wrong under consideration, are relevant facts.`
  line
  line `(b) The question is as to the date of A's birth. An entry in the diary of a deceased surgeon regularly kept in the course of business, stating that, on a given day he attended A's mother and delivered her of a son, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(c) The question is, whether A was in Nagpur on a given day. A statement in the diary of a deceased solicitor, regularly kept in the course of business, that on a given day the solicitor attended A at a place mentioned, in Nagpur, for the purpose of conferring with him upon specified business, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(d) The question is, whether a ship sailed from Mumbai harbour on a given day. A letter written by a deceased member of a merchant's firm by which she was chartered to their correspondents in Chennai, to whom the cargo was consigned, stating that the ship sailed on a given day from Mumbai port, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(e) The question is, whether rent was paid to A for certain land. A letter from A's deceased agent to A, saying that he had received the rent on A's account and held it at A's orders is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(f) The question is, whether A and B were legally married. The statement of a deceased clergyman that he married them under such circumstances that the celebration would be a crime is relevant.`
  line
  line `(g) The question is, whether A, a person who cannot be found, wrote a letter on a certain day. The fact that a letter written by him is dated on that day is relevant.`
  line
  line `(h) The question is, what was the cause of the wreck of a ship. A protest made by the captain, whose attendance cannot be procured, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(i) The question is, whether a given road is a public way. A statement by A, a deceased headman of the village, that the road was public, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(j) The question is, what was the price of grain on a certain day in a particular market. A statement of the price, made by a deceased business person in the ordinary course of his business, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(k) The question is, whether A, who is dead, was the father of B. A statement by A that B was his son, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(l) The question is, what was the date of the birth of A. A letter from A's deceased father to a friend, announcing the birth of A on a given day, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(m) The question is, whether, and when, A and B were married. An entry in a memorandum book by C, the deceased father of B, of his daughter's marriage with A on a given date, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `(n) A sues B for a libel expressed in a painted caricature exposed in a shop window. The question is as to the similarity of the caricature and its libellous character. The remarks of a crowd of spectators on these points may be proved.`
obj_root_law_sections_26_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_27:
  sectionId (90941)
  sectionNo (27)
  orderNo 27
  title `Relevancy of certain evidence for proving, in subsequent proceeding, truth of facts therein stated.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_27_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_27_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90941&sectionno=27&orderno=27&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_27_content:
  string
  line `Evidence given by a witness in a judicial proceeding, or before any person authorised by law to`
  line `take it, is relevant for the purpose of proving, in a subsequent judicial proceeding, or in a later stage of the`
  line `same judicial proceeding, the truth of the facts which it states, when the witness is dead or cannot be`
  line `found, or is incapable of giving evidence, or is kept out of the way by the adverse party, or if his presence`
  line `cannot be obtained without an amount of delay or expense which, under the circumstances of the case,`
  line `the Court considers unreasonable:`
  line
  line `Provided that the proceeding was between the same parties or their representatives in interest; that the`
  line `adverse party in the first proceeding had the right and opportunity to cross-examine and the questions in`
  line `issue were substantially the same in the first as in the second proceeding.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--A criminal trial or inquiry shall be deemed to be a proceeding between the prosecutor and the accused within the meaning of this section.`
obj_root_law_sections_27_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_28:
  sectionId (90794)
  sectionNo (28)
  orderNo 28
  title `Entries in books of account when relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_28_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90794&sectionno=28&orderno=28&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_28_content:
  string
  line `Entries in the books of account, including those`
  line `maintained in an electronic form, regularly kept in the course of business are relevant whenever they refer`
  line `to a matter into which the Court has to inquire, but such statements shall not alone be sufficient evidence`
  line `to charge any person with liability.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A sues B for one thousand rupees, and shows entries in his account books showing B to be indebted`
  line `to him to this amount. The entries are relevant, but are not sufficient, without other evidence, to prove the`
  line debt.
obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_29:
  sectionId (90795)
  sectionNo (29)
  orderNo 29
  title `Relevancy of entry in public record or an electronic record made in performance of duty.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_29_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_29_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90795&sectionno=29&orderno=29&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_29_content:
  string
  line `An entry in any public or other official book, register or record or an electronic record, stating a fact in`
  line `issue or relevant fact, and made by a public servant in the discharge of his official duty, or by any other`
  line `person in performance of a duty specially enjoined by the law of the country in which such book, register`
  line `or record or an electronic record, is kept, is itself a relevant fact.`
obj_root_law_sections_29_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_30:
  sectionId (90796)
  sectionNo (30)
  orderNo 30
  title `Relevancy of statements in maps, charts and plans.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_30_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_30_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90796&sectionno=30&orderno=30&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_30_content:
  string
  line `Statements of facts in issue or relevant`
  line `facts, made in published maps or charts generally offered for public sale, or in maps or plans made under`
  line `the authority of the Central Government or any State Government, as to matters usually represented or`
  line `stated in such maps, charts or plans, are themselves relevant facts`
obj_root_law_sections_30_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_31:
  sectionId (90797)
  sectionNo (31)
  orderNo 31
  title `Relevancy of statement as to fact of public nature contained in certain Acts or notifications.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_31_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_31_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90797&sectionno=31&orderno=31&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_31_content:
  string
  line `When the Court has to form an opinion as to the existence of any fact of a public nature,`
  line `any statement of it, made in a recital contained in any Central Act or State Act or in a Central`
  line `Government or State Government notification appearing in the respective Official Gazette or in any`
  line `printed paper or in electronic or digital form purporting to be such Gazette, is a relevant fact.`
obj_root_law_sections_31_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_32:
  sectionId (90942)
  sectionNo (32)
  orderNo 32
  title `Relevancy of statements as to any law contained in law books including electronic or digital form.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_32_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_32_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90942&sectionno=32&orderno=32&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_32_content:
  string
  line `When the Court has to form an opinion as to a law of any country, any statement of such law`
  line `contained in a book purporting to be printed or published including in electronic or digital form under the`
  line `authority of the Government of such country and to contain any such law, and any report of a ruling of`
  line `the Courts of such country contained in a book including in electronic or digital form purporting to be a`
  line `report of such rulings, is relevant.`
obj_root_law_sections_32_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_33:
  sectionId (90943)
  sectionNo (33)
  orderNo 33
  title `What evidence to be given when statement forms part of a conversation, document, electronic record, book or series of letters or papers.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_33_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_33_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90943&sectionno=33&orderno=33&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_33_content:
  string
  line `When any statement of which evidence is given`
  line `forms part of a longer statement, or of a conversation or part of an isolated document, or is contained in a`
  line `document which forms part of a book, or is contained in part of electronic record or of a connected series`
  line `of letters or papers, evidence shall be given of so much and no more of the statement, conversation,`
  line `document, electronic record, book or series of letters or papers as the Court considers necessary in that`
  line `particular case to the full understanding of the nature and effect of the statement, and of the`
  line `circumstances under which it was made.`
obj_root_law_sections_33_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_34:
  sectionId (90800)
  sectionNo (34)
  orderNo 34
  title `Previous judgments relevant to bar a second suit or trial.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_34_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_34_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90800&sectionno=34&orderno=34&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_34_content:
  string
  line `The existence of any judgment,`
  line `order or decree which by law prevents any Court from taking cognizance of a suit or holding a trial, is a relevant fact when the question is whether such Court ought to take cognizance of such suit or to hold`
  line `such trial.`
obj_root_law_sections_34_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_35:
  sectionId (90801)
  sectionNo (35)
  orderNo 35
  title `Relevancy of certain judgments in probate, etc., jurisdiction.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_35_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_35_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90801&sectionno=35&orderno=35&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_35_content:
  string
  line `(1) A final judgment, order or`
  line `decree of a competent Court or Tribunal, in the exercise of probate, matrimonial, admiralty or insolvency`
  line `jurisdiction, which confers upon or takes away from any person any legal character, or which declares`
  line `any person to be entitled to any such character, or to be entitled to any specific thing, not as against any`
  line `specified person but absolutely, is relevant when the existence of any such legal character, or the title of`
  line `any such person to any such thing, is relevant.`
  line
  line `(2) Such judgment, order or decree is conclusive proof that--`
  line
  line `(i) any legal character, which it confers accrued at the time when such judgment, order or decree`
  line `came into operation;`
  line
  line `(ii) any legal character, to which it declares any such person to be entitled, accrued to that person`
  line `at the time when such judgment, order or decree declares it to have accrued to that person;`
  line
  line `(iii) any legal character which it takes away from any such person ceased at the time from which`
  line `such judgment, order or decree declared that it had ceased or should cease; and`
  line
  line `(iv) anything to which it declares any person to be so entitled was the property of that person at`
  line `the time from which such judgment, order or decree declares that it had been or should be his`
  line property.
obj_root_law_sections_35_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_36:
  sectionId (90944)
  sectionNo (36)
  orderNo 36
  title `Relevancy and effect of judgments, orders or decrees, other than those mentioned in section 35.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_36_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_36_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90944&sectionno=36&orderno=36&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_36_content:
  string
  line `Judgments, orders or decrees other than those mentioned in section 35 are relevant if they`
  line `relate to matters of a public nature relevant to the enquiry; but such judgments, orders or decrees are not`
  line `conclusive proof of that which they state.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A sues B for trespass on his land. B alleges the existence of a public right of way over the land,`
  line `which A denies. The existence of a decree in favour of the defendant, in a suit by A against C for a`
  line `trespass on the same land, in which C alleged the existence of the same right of way, is relevant, but it is`
  line `not conclusive proof that the right of way exists.`
obj_root_law_sections_36_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_37:
  sectionId (90803)
  sectionNo (37)
  orderNo 37
  title `Judgments, etc., other than those mentioned in sections 34, 35 and 36 when relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_37_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_37_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90803&sectionno=37&orderno=37&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_37_content:
  string
  line `Judgments or orders or decrees, other than those mentioned in sections 34, 35 and 36, are irrelevant,`
  line `unless the existence of such judgment, order or decree is a fact in issue, or is relevant under some other`
  line `provision of this Adhiniyam.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A and B separately sue C for a libel which reflects upon each of them. C in each case says that the`
  line `matter alleged to be libellous is true, and the circumstances are such that it is probably true in each case,`
  line `or in neither. A obtains a decree against C for damages on the ground that C failed to make out his`
  line `justification. The fact is irrelevant as between B and C.`
  line
  line `(b) A prosecutes B for stealing a cow from him. B is convicted. A afterwards sues C for the cow,`
  line `which B had sold to him before his conviction. As between A and C, the judgment against B is irrelevant.`
  line
  line `(c) A has obtained a decree for the possession of land against B. C, B's son, murders A in`
  line `consequence. The existence of the judgment is relevant, as showing motive for a crime.`
  line
  line `(d) A is charged with theft and with having been previously convicted of theft. The previous`
  line `conviction is relevant as a fact in issue.`
  line
  line `(e) A is tried for the murder of B. The fact that B prosecuted A for libel and that A was convicted and`
  line `sentenced is relevant under section 6 as showing the motive for the fact in issue.`
obj_root_law_sections_37_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_38:
  sectionId (90804)
  sectionNo (38)
  orderNo 38
  title `Fraud or collusion in obtaining judgment, or incompetency of Court, may be proved.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_38_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_38_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90804&sectionno=38&orderno=38&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_38_content:
  string
  line Any
  line `party to a suit or other proceeding may show that any judgment, order or decree which is relevant under`
  line `section 34, 35 or 36, and which has been proved by the adverse party, was delivered by a Court not`
  line `competent to deliver it, or was obtained by fraud or collusion.`
obj_root_law_sections_38_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_39:
  sectionId (90805)
  sectionNo (39)
  orderNo 39
  title `Opinions of experts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_39_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_39_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90805&sectionno=39&orderno=39&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_39_content:
  string
  line `(1) When the Court has to form an opinion upon a point of foreign law or`
  line `of science or art, or any other field, or as to identity of handwriting or finger impressions, the opinions`
  line `upon that point of persons specially skilled in such foreign law, science or art, or any other field, or in`
  line `questions as to identity of handwriting or finger impressions are relevant facts and such persons are called`
  line experts.
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) The question is, whether the death of A was caused by poison. The opinions of experts as to the`
  line `symptoms produced by the poison by which A is supposed to have died, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(b) The question is, whether A, at the time of doing a certain act, was, by reason of unsoundness of`
  line `mind, incapable of knowing the nature of the act, or that he was doing what was either wrong or contrary`
  line `to law. The opinions of experts upon the question whether the symptoms exhibited by A commonly show`
  line `unsoundness of mind, and whether such unsoundness of mind usually renders persons incapable of`
  line `knowing the nature of the acts which they do, or of knowing that what they do is either wrong or contrary`
  line `to law, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(c) The question is, whether a certain document was written by A. Another document is produced`
  line `which is proved or admitted to have been written by A. The opinions of experts on the question whether`
  line `the two documents were written by the same person or by different persons, are relevant.`
  line
  line `(2) When in a proceeding, the court has to form an opinion on any matter relating to any information`
  line `transmitted or stored in any computer resource or any other electronic or digital form, the opinion of the`
  line `Examiner of Electronic Evidence referred to in section 79A of the Information Technology Act, 2000`
  line `(21 of 2000), is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--For the purposes of this sub-section, an Examiner of Electronic Evidence shall be an`
  line expert.
obj_root_law_sections_39_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_40:
  sectionId (90806)
  sectionNo (40)
  orderNo 40
  title `Facts bearing upon opinions of experts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_40_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_40_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90806&sectionno=40&orderno=40&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_40_content:
  string
  line `Facts, not otherwise relevant, are relevant if they`
  line `support or are inconsistent with the opinions of experts, when such opinions are relevant.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) The question is, whether A was poisoned by a certain poison. The fact that other persons, who`
  line `were poisoned by that poison, exhibited certain symptoms which experts affirm or deny to be the`
  line `symptoms of that poison, is relevant.`
  line
  line `(b) The question is, whether an obstruction to a harbour is caused by a certain sea-wall. The fact that`
  line `other harbours similarly situated in other respects, but where there were no such sea-walls, began to be`
  line `obstructed at about the same time, is relevant.`
obj_root_law_sections_40_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_41:
  sectionId (90807)
  sectionNo (41)
  orderNo 41
  title `Opinion as to handwriting and signature, when relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_41_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_41_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90807&sectionno=41&orderno=41&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_41_content:
  string
  line `(1) When the Court has to form an`
  line `opinion as to the person by whom any document was written or signed, the opinion of any person`
  line `acquainted with the handwriting of the person by whom it is supposed to be written or signed that it was`
  line `or was not written or signed by that person, is a relevant fact.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--A person is said to be acquainted with the handwriting of another person when he has`
  line `seen that person write, or when he has received documents purporting to be written by that person in`
  line `answer to documents written by himself or under his authority and addressed to that person, or when, in`
  line `the ordinary course of business, documents purporting to be written by that person have been habitually`
  line `submitted to him.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `The question is, whether a given letter is in the handwriting of A, a merchant in Itanagar. B is a`
  line `merchant in Bengaluru, who has written letters addressed to A and received letters purporting to be`
  line `written by him. C, is B's clerk whose duty it was to examine and file B's correspondence. D is B's broker,`
  line `to whom B habitually submitted the letters purporting to be written by A for the purpose of advising him`
  line `thereon. The opinions of B, C and D on the question whether the letter is in the handwriting of A are`
  line `relevant, though neither B, C nor D ever saw A write.`
  line
  line `(2) When the Court has to form an opinion as to the electronic signature of any person, the opinion of`
  line `the Certifying Authority which has issued the Electronic Signature Certificate is a relevant fact.`
obj_root_law_sections_41_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_42:
  sectionId (90808)
  sectionNo (42)
  orderNo 42
  title `Opinion as to existence of general custom or right, when relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_42_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_42_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90808&sectionno=42&orderno=42&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_42_content:
  string
  line `When the Court has to`
  line `form an opinion as to the existence of any general custom or right, the opinions, as to the existence of`
  line `such custom or right, of persons who would be likely to know of its existence if it existed, are relevant`
  line
  line `Explanation.--The expression “general custom or right” includes customs or rights common to any considerable class of persons.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `The right of the villagers of a particular village to use the water of a particular well is a general right`
  line `within the meaning of this section.`
obj_root_law_sections_42_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_43:
  sectionId (90809)
  sectionNo (43)
  orderNo 43
  title `Opinion as to usages, tenets, etc., when relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_43_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_43_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90809&sectionno=43&orderno=43&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_43_content:
  string
  line `When the Court has to form an opinion as`
  line to—
  line
  line `(i) the usages and tenets of any body of men or family;`
  line
  line `(ii) the constitution and governance of any religious or charitable foundation; or`
  line
  line `(iii) the meaning of words or terms used in particular districts or by particular classes of people,`
  line
  line `the opinions of persons having special means of knowledge thereon, are relevant facts.`
obj_root_law_sections_43_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_44:
  sectionId (90810)
  sectionNo (44)
  orderNo 44
  title `Opinion on relationship, when relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_44_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_44_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90810&sectionno=44&orderno=44&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_44_content:
  string
  line `When the Court has to form an opinion as to the`
  line `relationship of one person to another, the opinion, expressed by conduct, as to the existence of such`
  line `relationship, of any person who, as a member of the family or otherwise, has special means of knowledge`
  line `on the subject, is a relevant fact:`
  line
  line `Provided that such opinion shall not be sufficient to prove a marriage in proceedings under the`
  line `Divorce Act, 1869 (4 of 1869), or in prosecution under sections 82 and 84 of the Bharatiya Nyaya`
  line `Sanhita, 2023.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) The question is, whether A and B were married. The fact that they were usually received and`
  line `treated by their friends as husband and wife, is relevant.`
  line
  line `(b) The question is, whether A was the legitimate son of B. The fact that A was always treated as`
  line `such by members of the family, is relevant.`
obj_root_law_sections_44_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_45:
  sectionId (90811)
  sectionNo (45)
  orderNo 45
  title `Grounds of opinion, when relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_45_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_45_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90811&sectionno=45&orderno=45&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_45_content:
  string
  line `Whenever the opinion of any living person is relevant,`
  line `the grounds on which such opinion is based are also relevant.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `An expert may give an account of experiments performed by him for the purpose of forming his`
  line opinion.
obj_root_law_sections_45_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_46:
  sectionId (90812)
  sectionNo (46)
  orderNo 46
  title `In civil cases character to prove conduct imputed, irrelevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_46_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_46_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90812&sectionno=46&orderno=46&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_46_content:
  string
  line `In civil cases the fact that the`
  line `character of any person concerned is such as to render probable or improbable any conduct imputed to`
  line `him, is irrelevant, except in so far as such character appears from facts otherwise relevant.`
obj_root_law_sections_46_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_47:
  sectionId (90813)
  sectionNo (47)
  orderNo 47
  title `In criminal cases previous good character relevant.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_47_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_47_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90813&sectionno=47&orderno=47&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_47_content:
  string
  line `In criminal proceedings the fact that the`
  line `person accused is of a good character, is relevant.`
obj_root_law_sections_47_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_48:
  sectionId (90814)
  sectionNo (48)
  orderNo 48
  title `Evidence of character or previous sexual experience not relevant in certain cases.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_48_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_48_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90814&sectionno=48&orderno=48&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_48_content:
  string
  line `In a`
  line `prosecution for an offence under section 64, section 65, section 66, section 67, section 68,`
  line `section 69, section 70, section 71, section 74, section 75, section 76, section 77 or section 78 of the`
  line `Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023 or for attempt to commit any such offence, where the question of consent`
  line `is in issue, evidence of the character of the victim or of such person’s previous sexual experience with`
  line `any person shall not be relevant on the issue of such consent or the quality of consent.`
obj_root_law_sections_48_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_49:
  sectionId (90815)
  sectionNo (49)
  orderNo 49
  title `Previous bad character not relevant, except in reply.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_49_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_49_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90815&sectionno=49&orderno=49&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_49_content:
  string
  line `In criminal proceedings, the fact that`
  line `the accused has a bad character, is irrelevant, unless evidence has been given that he has a good character,`
  line `in which case it becomes relevant`
  line
  line `Explanation 1.--This section does not apply to cases in which the bad character of any person is`
  line `itself a fact in issue.`
  line
  line `Explanation 2.--A previous conviction is relevant as evidence of bad character`
obj_root_law_sections_49_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_50:
  sectionId (90816)
  sectionNo (50)
  orderNo 50
  title `Character as affecting damages.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_50_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_50_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90816&sectionno=50&orderno=50&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_50_content:
  string
  line `In civil cases, the fact that the character of any person is such`
  line `as to affect the amount of damages which he ought to receive, is relevant.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--In this section and sections 46, 47 and 49, the word "character" includes both`
  line `reputation and disposition; but, except as provided in section 49, evidence may be given only of general`
  line `reputation and general disposition, and not of particular acts by which reputation or disposition has been`
  line shown.
obj_root_law_sections_50_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_51:
  sectionId (90818)
  sectionNo (51)
  orderNo 51
  title `Fact judicially noticeable need not be proved.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_51_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_51_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90818&sectionno=51&orderno=51&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_51_content:
  string
  line `No fact of which the Court will take judicial`
  line `notice need be proved.`
obj_root_law_sections_51_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_52:
  sectionId (90819)
  sectionNo (52)
  orderNo 52
  title `Facts of which Court shall take judicial notice.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_52_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_52_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90819&sectionno=52&orderno=52&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_52_content:
  string
  line `(1) The Court shall take judicial notice of the`
  line `following facts, namely:--`
  line
  line `(a) all laws in force in the territory of India including laws having extra-territorial operation;`
  line
  line `(b) international treaty, agreement or convention with country or countries by India, or decisions`
  line `made by India at international associations or other bodies;`
  line
  line `(c) the course of proceeding of the Constituent Assembly of India, of Parliament of India and of`
  line `the State Legislatures;`
  line
  line `(d) the seals of all Courts and Tribunals;`
  line
  line `(e) the seals of Courts of Admiralty and Maritime Jurisdiction, Notaries Public, and all seals`
  line `which any person is authorised to use by the Constitution, or by an Act of Parliament or State`
  line `Legislatures, or Regulations having the force of law in India;`
  line
  line `(f) the accession to office, names, titles, functions, and signatures of the persons filling for the`
  line `time being any public office in any State, if the fact of their appointment to such office is notified in`
  line `any Official Gazette;`
  line
  line `(g) the existence, title and national flag of every country or sovereign recognised by the`
  line `Government of India;`
  line
  line `(h) the divisions of time, the geographical divisions of the world, and public festivals, fasts and`
  line `holidays notified in the Official Gazette;`
  line
  line `(i) the territory of India;`
  line
  line `(j) the commencement, continuance and termination of hostilities between the Government of`
  line `India and any other country or body of persons;`
  line
  line `(k) the names of the members and officers of the Court and of their deputies and subordinate`
  line `officers and assistants, and also of all officers acting in execution of its process, and of advocates and`
  line `other persons authorised by law to appear or act before it;`
  line
  line `(l) the rule of the road on land or at sea`
  line
  line `(2) In the cases referred to in sub-section (1) and also on all matters of public history, literature,`
  line `science or art, the Court may resort for its aid to appropriate books or documents of reference and if the`
  line `Court is called upon by any person to take judicial notice of any fact, it may refuse to do so unless and`
  line `until such person produces any such book or document as it may consider necessary to enable it to do so.`
obj_root_law_sections_52_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_53:
  sectionId (90820)
  sectionNo (53)
  orderNo 53
  title `Facts admitted need not be proved.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_53_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_53_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90820&sectionno=53&orderno=53&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_53_content:
  string
  line `No fact needs to be proved in any proceeding which the`
  line `parties thereto or their agents agree to admit at the hearing, or which, before the hearing, they agree to`
  line `admit by any writing under their hands, or which by any rule of pleading in force at the time they are`
  line `deemed to have admitted by their pleadings:`
  line
  line `Provided that the Court may, in its discretion, require the facts admitted to be proved otherwise than`
  line `by such admissions.`
obj_root_law_sections_53_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_54:
  sectionId (90821)
  sectionNo (54)
  orderNo 54
  title `Proof of facts by oral evidence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_54_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_54_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90821&sectionno=54&orderno=54&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_54_content:
  string
  line `All facts, except the contents of documents may be proved by`
  line `oral evidence.`
obj_root_law_sections_54_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_55:
  sectionId (90822)
  sectionNo (55)
  orderNo 55
  title `Oral evidence to be direct.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_55_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_55_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90822&sectionno=55&orderno=55&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_55_content:
  string
  line `Oral evidence shall, in all cases whatever, be direct; if it refers`
  line to,--
  line
  line `(i) a fact which could be seen, it must be the evidence of a witness who says he saw it;`
  line
  line `(ii) a fact which could be heard, it must be the evidence of a witness who says he heard it;`
  line
  line `(iii) a fact which could be perceived by any other sense or in any other manner, it must be the`
  line `evidence of a witness who says he perceived it by that sense or in that manner;`
  line
  line `(iv) an opinion or to the grounds on which that opinion is held, it must be the evidence of the`
  line `person who holds that opinion on those grounds:`
  line
  line `Provided that the opinions of experts expressed in any treatise commonly offered for sale, and the`
  line `grounds on which such opinions are held, may be proved by the production of such treatises if the author`
  line `is dead or cannot be found, or has become incapable of giving evidence, or cannot be called as a witness`
  line `without an amount of delay or expense which the Court regards as unreasonable:`
  line
  line `Provided further that, if oral evidence refers to the existence or condition of any material thing other`
  line `than a document, the Court may, if it thinks fit, require the production of such material thing for its`
  line inspection.
obj_root_law_sections_55_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_56:
  sectionId (90823)
  sectionNo (56)
  orderNo 56
  title `Proof of contents of documents.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_56_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_56_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90823&sectionno=56&orderno=56&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_56_content:
  string
  line `The contents of documents may be proved either by primary`
  line `or by secondary evidence.`
obj_root_law_sections_56_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_57:
  sectionId (90824)
  sectionNo (57)
  orderNo 57
  title `Primary evidence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_57_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_57_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90824&sectionno=57&orderno=57&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_57_content:
  string
  line `Primary evidence means the document itself produced for the inspection of`
  line `the Court.`
  line
  line `Explanation 1.--Where a document is executed in several parts, each part is primary evidence of`
  line `the document.`
  line
  line `Explanation 2.--Where a document is executed in counterpart, each counterpart being executed`
  line `by one or some of the parties only, each counterpart is primary evidence as against the parties`
  line `executing it`
  line
  line `Explanation 3.--Where a number of documents are all made by one uniform process, as in the`
  line `case of printing, lithography or photography, each is primary evidence of the contents of the rest; but,`
  line `where they are all copies of a common original, they are not primary evidence of the contents of the`
  line original.
  line
  line `Explanation 4.--Where an electronic or digital record is created or stored, and such storage`
  line `occurs simultaneously or sequentially in multiple files, each such file is primary evidence.`
  line
  line `Explanation 5.--Where an electronic or digital record is produced from proper custody, such`
  line `electronic and digital record is primary evidence unless it is disputed.`
  line
  line `Explanation 6.--Where a video recording is simultaneously stored in electronic form and`
  line `transmitted or broadcast or transferred to another, each of the stored recordings is primary evidence.`
  line
  line `Explanation 7.--Where an electronic or digital record is stored in multiple storage spaces in a`
  line `computer resource, each such automated storage, including temporary files, is primary evidence.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A person is shown to have been in possession of a number of placards, all printed at one time from`
  line `one original. Any one of the placards is primary evidence of the contents of any other, but no one of them`
  line `is primary evidence of the contents of the original.`
obj_root_law_sections_57_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_58:
  sectionId (90825)
  sectionNo (58)
  orderNo 58
  title `Secondary evidence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_58_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_58_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90825&sectionno=58&orderno=58&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_58_content:
  string
  line `Secondary evidence includes--`
  line
  line `(i) certified copies given under the provisions hereinafter contained;`
  line
  line `(ii) copies made from the original by mechanical processes which in themselves ensure the`
  line `accuracy of the copy, and copies compared with such copies;`
  line
  line `(iii) copies made from or compared with the original`
  line
  line `(iv) counterparts of documents as against the parties who did not execute them;`
  line
  line `(v) oral accounts of the contents of a document given by some person who has himself seen it;`
  line
  line `(vi) oral admissions;`
  line
  line `(vii) written admissions;`
  line
  line `(viii) evidence of a person who has examined a document, the original of which consists of`
  line `numerous accounts or other documents which cannot conveniently be examined in Court, and who is`
  line `skilled in the examination of such documents.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A photograph of an original is secondary evidence of its contents, though the two have not been`
  line `compared, if it is proved that the thing photographed was the original.`
  line
  line `(b) A copy compared with a copy of a letter made by a copying machine is secondary evidence of the`
  line `contents of the letter, if it is shown that the copy made by the copying machine was made from the`
  line original.
  line
  line `(c) A copy transcribed from a copy, but afterwards compared with the original, is secondary`
  line `evidence; but the copy not so compared is not secondary evidence of the original, although the copy from`
  line `which it was transcribed was compared with the original.`
  line
  line `(d) Neither an oral account of a copy compared with the original, nor an oral account of a photograph`
  line `or machine-copy of the original, is secondary evidence of the original.`
obj_root_law_sections_58_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_59:
  sectionId (90826)
  sectionNo (59)
  orderNo 59
  title `Proof of documents by primary evidence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_59_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_59_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90826&sectionno=59&orderno=59&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_59_content:
  string
  line `Documents shall be proved by primary`
  line `evidence except in the cases hereinafter mentioned`
obj_root_law_sections_59_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_60:
  sectionId (90827)
  sectionNo (60)
  orderNo 60
  title `Cases in which secondary evidence relating to documents maybe given.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_60_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_60_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90827&sectionno=60&orderno=60&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_60_content:
  string
  line Secondary
  line `evidence may be given of the existence, condition, or contents of a document in the following cases,`
  line `namely:--`
  line
  line `(a) when the original is shown or appears to be in the possession or power--`
  line
  line `(i) of the person against whom the document is sought to be proved; or`
  line
  line `(ii) of any person out of reach of, or not subject to, the process of the Court; or`
  line
  line `(iii) of any person legally bound to produce it,`
  line
  line `and when, after the notice mentioned in section 64 such person does not produce it;`
  line
  line `(b) when the existence, condition or contents of the original have been proved to be admitted in`
  line `writing by the person against whom it is proved or by his representative in interest;`
  line
  line `(c) when the original has been destroyed or lost, or when the party offering evidence of its`
  line `contents cannot, for any other reason not arising from his own default or neglect, produce it in`
  line `reasonable time;`
  line
  line `(d) when the original is of such a nature as not to be easily movable;`
  line
  line `(e) when the original is a public document within the meaning of section 74;`
  line
  line `(f) when the original is a document of which a certified copy is permitted by this Adhiniyam, or`
  line `by any other law in force in India to be given in evidence;`
  line
  line `(g) when the originals consist of numerous accounts or other documents which cannot`
  line `conveniently be examined in Court, and the fact to be proved is the general result of the whole`
  line collection.
  line
  line `Explanation.--For the purposes of--`
  line
  line `(i) clauses (a), (c) and (d), any secondary evidence of the contents of the document is admissible;`
  line
  line `(ii) clause (b), the written admission is admissible;`
  line
  line `(iii) clause (e) or (f), a certified copy of the document, but no other kind of secondary evidence, is`
  line admissible;
  line
  line `(iv) clause (g), evidence may be given as to the general result of the documents by any person`
  line `who has examined them, and who is skilled in the examination of such document.`
obj_root_law_sections_60_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_61:
  sectionId (90828)
  sectionNo (61)
  orderNo 61
  title `Electronic or digital record.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_61_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_61_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90828&sectionno=61&orderno=61&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_61_content:
  string
  line `Nothing in this Adhiniyam shall apply to deny the`
  line `admissibility of an electronic or digital record in the evidence on the ground that it is an electronic or`
  line `digital record and such record shall, subject to section 63, have the same legal effect, validity and`
  line `enforceability as other document.`
obj_root_law_sections_61_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_62:
  sectionId (90829)
  sectionNo (62)
  orderNo 62
  title `Special provisions as to evidence relating to electronic record.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_62_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_62_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90829&sectionno=62&orderno=62&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_62_content:
  string
  line `The contents of`
  line `electronic records may be proved in accordance with the provisions of section 63.`
obj_root_law_sections_62_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_63:
  sectionId (90830)
  sectionNo (63)
  orderNo 63
  title `Admissibility of electronic records.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_63_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_63_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90830&sectionno=63&orderno=63&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_63_content:
  string
  line `(1) Notwithstanding anything contained in this`
  line `Adhiniyam, any information contained in an electronic record which is printed on paper, stored, recorded`
  line `or copied in optical or magnetic media or semiconductor memory which is produced by a computer or`
  line `any communication device or otherwise stored, recorded or copied in any electronic form (hereinafter`
  line `referred to as the computer output) shall be deemed to be also a document, if the conditions mentioned in`
  line `this section are satisfied in relation to the information and computer in question and shall be admissible in`
  line `any proceedings, without further proof or production of the original, as evidence or any contents of the`
  line `original or of any fact stated therein of which direct evidence would be admissible.`
  line
  line `(2) The conditions referred to in sub-section (1) in respect of a computer output shall be the`
  line `following, namely:---`
  line
  line `(a) the computer output containing the information was produced by the computer or`
  line `communication device during the period over which the computer or Communication device was`
  line `used regularly to create, store or process information for the purposes of any activity regularly carried`
  line `on over that period by the person having lawful control over the use of the computer or`
  line `communication device;`
  line
  line `(b) during the said period, information of the kind contained in the electronic record or of the`
  line `kind from which the information so contained is derived was regularly fed into the computer or`
  line `Communication device in the ordinary course of the said activities;`
  line
  line `(c) throughout the material part of the said period, the computer or communication device was`
  line `operating properly or, if not, then in respect of any period in which it was not operating properly or`
  line `was out of operation during that part of the period, was not such as to affect the electronic record or`
  line `the accuracy of its contents; and`
  line
  line `(d) the information contained in the electronic record reproduces or is derived from such`
  line `information fed into the computer or Communication device in the ordinary course of the said`
  line activities.
  line
  line `(3) Where over any period, the function of creating, storing or processing information for the`
  line `purposes of any activity regularly carried on over that period as mentioned in clause (a) of sub-section (2)`
  line `was regularly performed by means of one or more computers or communication device, whether--`
  line
  line `(a) in standalone mode; or`
  line
  line `(b) on a computer system; or`
  line
  line `(c) on a computer network; or`
  line
  line `(d) on a computer resource enabling information creation or providing information processing`
  line `and storage; or`
  line
  line `(e) through an intermediary,`
  line
  line `all the computers or communication devices used for that purpose during that period shall be treated for`
  line `the purposes of this section as constituting a single computer or communication device; and references in`
  line `this section to a computer or communication device shall be construed accordingly.`
  line
  line `(4) In any proceeding where it is desired to give a statement in evidence by virtue of this section, a`
  line `certificate doing any of the following things shall be submitted along with the electronic record at each`
  line `instance where it is being submitted for admission, namely:--`
  line
  line `(a) identifying the electronic record containing the statement and describing the manner in which`
  line `it was produced;`
  line
  line `(b) giving such particulars of any device involved in the production of that electronic record as`
  line `may be appropriate for the purpose of showing that the electronic record was produced by a computer`
  line `or a communication device referred to in clauses (a) to (e) of sub-section (3);`
  line
  line `(c) dealing with any of the matters to which the conditions mentioned in sub-section (2) relate,`
  line
  line `and purporting to be signed by a person in charge of the computer or communication device or the`
  line `management of the relevant activities (whichever is appropriate) and an expert shall be evidence of any`
  line `matter stated in the certificate; and for the purposes of this sub-section it shall be sufficient for a matter to`
  line `be stated to the best of the knowledge and belief of the person stating it in the certificate specified in the`
  line Schedule.
  line
  line `(5) For the purposes of this section,---`
  line
  line `(a) information shall be taken to be supplied to a computer or communication device if it is`
  line `supplied thereto in any appropriate form and whether it is so supplied directly or (with or without`
  line `human intervention) by means of any appropriate equipment;`
  line
  line `(b) a computer output shall be taken to have been produced by a computer or communication`
  line `device whether it was produced by it directly or (with or without human intervention) by means of`
  line `any appropriate equipment or by other electronic means as referred to in clauses (a) to (e) of`
  line `sub-section (3).`
obj_root_law_sections_63_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_64:
  sectionId (90831)
  sectionNo (64)
  orderNo 64
  title `Rules as to notice to produce.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_64_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_64_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90831&sectionno=64&orderno=64&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_64_content:
  string
  line `Secondary evidence of the contents of the documents referred to`
  line `in clause (a) of section 60, shall not be given unless the party proposing to give such secondary evidence`
  line `has previously given to the party in whose possession or power the document is, or to his advocate or`
  line `representative, such notice to produce it as is prescribed by law; and if no notice is prescribed by law,`
  line `then such notice as the Court considers reasonable under the circumstances of the case:`
  line
  line `Provided that such notice shall not be required in order to render secondary evidence admissible in`
  line `any of the following cases, or in any other case in which the Court thinks fit to dispense with it:---`
  line
  line `(a) when the document to be proved is itself a notice;`
  line
  line `(b) when, from the nature of the case, the adverse party must know that he will be required to`
  line `produce it;`
  line
  line `(c) when it appears or is proved that the adverse party has obtained possession of the original by`
  line `fraud or force;`
  line
  line `(d) when the adverse party or his agent has the original in Court;`
  line
  line `(e) when the adverse party or his agent has admitted the loss of the document;`
  line
  line `(f) when the person in possession of the document is out of reach of, or not subject to, the process`
  line `of the Court.`
obj_root_law_sections_64_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_65:
  sectionId (90945)
  sectionNo (65)
  orderNo 65
  title `Proof of signature and handwriting of person alleged to have signed or written document produced.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_65_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_65_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90945&sectionno=65&orderno=65&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_65_content:
  string
  line `If a document is alleged to be signed or to have been written wholly or in part by any person,`
  line `the signature or the handwriting of so much of the document as is alleged to be in that person's`
  line `handwriting must be proved to be in his handwriting.`
obj_root_law_sections_65_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_66:
  sectionId (90833)
  sectionNo (66)
  orderNo 66
  title `Proof as to electronic signature.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_66_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_66_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90833&sectionno=66&orderno=66&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_66_content:
  string
  line `Except in the case of a secure electronic signature, if the`
  line `electronic signature of any subscriber is alleged to have been affixed to an electronic record, the fact that`
  line `such electronic signature is the electronic signature of the subscriber must be proved.`
obj_root_law_sections_66_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_67:
  sectionId (90834)
  sectionNo (67)
  orderNo 67
  title `Proof of execution of document required by law to be attested.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_67_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_67_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90834&sectionno=67&orderno=67&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_67_content:
  string
  line `If a document is required by`
  line `law to be attested, it shall not be used as evidence until one attesting witness at least has been called for the`
  line `purpose of proving its execution, if there be an attesting witness alive, and subject to the process of the`
  line `Court and capable of giving evidence:`
  line
  line `Provided that it shall not be necessary to call an attesting witness in proof of the execution of any`
  line `document, not being a will, which has been registered in accordance with the provisions of the Indian`
  line `Registration Act, 1908 (16 of 1908), unless its execution by the person by whom it purports to have been`
  line `executed is specifically denied.`
obj_root_law_sections_67_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_68:
  sectionId (90835)
  sectionNo (68)
  orderNo 68
  title `Proof where no attesting witness found.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_68_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_68_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90835&sectionno=68&orderno=68&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_68_content:
  string
  line `If no such attesting witness can be found, it must be`
  line `proved that the attestation of one attesting witness at least is in his handwriting, and that the signature of`
  line `the person executing the document is in the handwriting of that person`
obj_root_law_sections_68_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_69:
  sectionId (90836)
  sectionNo (69)
  orderNo 69
  title `Admission of execution by party to attested document.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_69_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_69_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90836&sectionno=69&orderno=69&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_69_content:
  string
  line `The admission of a party to an`
  line `attested document of its execution by himself shall be sufficient proof of its execution as against him,`
  line `though it be a document required by law to be attested.`
obj_root_law_sections_69_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_70:
  sectionId (90837)
  sectionNo (70)
  orderNo 70
  title `Proof when attesting witness denies execution.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_70_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_70_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90837&sectionno=70&orderno=70&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_70_content:
  string
  line `If the attesting witness denies or does not`
  line `recollect the execution of the document, its execution may be proved by other evidence.`
obj_root_law_sections_70_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_71:
  sectionId (90838)
  sectionNo (71)
  orderNo 71
  title `Proof of document not required by law to be attested.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_71_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_71_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90838&sectionno=71&orderno=71&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_71_content:
  string
  line `An attested document not required by`
  line `law to be attested may be proved as if it was unattested.`
obj_root_law_sections_71_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_72:
  sectionId (90839)
  sectionNo (72)
  orderNo 72
  title `Comparison of signature, writing or seal with others admitted or proved.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_72_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_72_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90839&sectionno=72&orderno=72&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_72_content:
  string
  line `(1) In order to`
  line `ascertain whether a signature, writing or seal is that of the person by whom it purports to have been`
  line `written or made, any signature, writing, or seal admitted or proved to the satisfaction of the Court to have`
  line `been written or made by that person may be compared with the one which is to be proved, although that`
  line `signature, writing or seal has not been produced or proved for any other purpose.`
  line
  line `(2) The Court may direct any person present in Court to write any words or figures for the purpose of`
  line `enabling the Court to compare the words or figures so written with any words or figures alleged to have`
  line `been written by such person.`
  line
  line `(3) This section applies also, with any necessary modifications, to finger impressions`
obj_root_law_sections_72_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_73:
  sectionId (90840)
  sectionNo (73)
  orderNo 73
  title `Proof as to verification of digital signature.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_73_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_73_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90840&sectionno=73&orderno=73&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_73_content:
  string
  line `In order to ascertain whether a digital signature is`
  line `that of the person by whom it purports to have been affixed, the Court may direct---`
  line
  line `(a) that person or the Controller or the Certifying Authority to produce the Digital Signature Certificate;`
  line
  line `(b) any other person to apply the public key listed in the Digital Signature Certificate and verify`
  line `the digital signature purported to have been affixed by that person.`
obj_root_law_sections_73_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_74:
  sectionId (90841)
  sectionNo (74)
  orderNo 74
  title `Public and private documents.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_74_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_74_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90841&sectionno=74&orderno=74&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_74_content:
  string
  line `(1) The following documents are public documents:--`
  line
  line `(a) documents forming the acts, or records of the acts--`
  line
  line `(i) of the sovereign authority;`
  line
  line `(ii) of official bodies and tribunals; and`
  line
  line `(iii) of public officers, legislative, judicial and executive of India or of a foreign country;`
  line
  line `(b) public records kept in any State or Union territory of private documents.`
  line
  line `(2) All other documents except the documents referred to in sub-section (1) are private.`
obj_root_law_sections_74_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_75:
  sectionId (90842)
  sectionNo (75)
  orderNo 75
  title `Certified copies of public documents.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_75_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_75_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90842&sectionno=75&orderno=75&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_75_content:
  string
  line `Every public officer having the custody of a public`
  line `document, which any person has a right to inspect, shall give that person on demand a copy of it on`
  line `payment of the legal fees therefor, together with a certificate written at the foot of such copy that it is a`
  line `true copy of such document or part thereof, as the case may be, and such certificate shall be dated and`
  line `subscribed by such officer with his name and his official title, and shall be sealed, whenever such officer`
  line `is authorised by law to make use of a seal; and such copies so certified shall be called certified copies`
  line
  line `Explanation.--Any officer who, by the ordinary course of official duty, is authorised to deliver such copies, shall be deemed to have the custody of such documents within the meaning of this section.`
obj_root_law_sections_75_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_76:
  sectionId (90843)
  sectionNo (76)
  orderNo 76
  title `Proof of documents by production of certified copies.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_76_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_76_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90843&sectionno=76&orderno=76&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_76_content:
  string
  line `Such certified copies may be produced`
  line `in proof of the contents of the public documents or parts of the public documents of which they purport to`
  line `be copies.`
obj_root_law_sections_76_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_77:
  sectionId (90844)
  sectionNo (77)
  orderNo 77
  title `Proof of other official documents.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_77_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_77_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90844&sectionno=77&orderno=77&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_77_content:
  string
  line `The following public documents may be proved as`
  line `follows: --`
  line
  line `(a) Acts, orders or notifications of the Central Government in any of its Ministries and`
  line `Departments or of any State Government or any Department of any State Government or Union`
  line `territory Administration--`
  line
  line `(i) by the records of the Departments, certified by the head of those Departments respectively; or`
  line
  line `(ii) by any document purporting to be printed by order of any such Government;`
  line
  line `(b) the proceedings of Parliament or a State Legislature, by the journals of those bodies`
  line `respectively, or by published Acts or abstracts, or by copies purporting to be printed by order of the`
  line `Government concerned;`
  line
  line `(c) proclamations, orders or Regulations issued by the President of India or the Governor of a`
  line `State or the Administrator or Lieutenant Governor of a Union territory, by copies or extracts`
  line `contained in the Official Gazette;`
  line
  line `(d) the Acts of the Executive or the proceedings of the Legislature of a foreign country, by`
  line `journals published by their authority, or commonly received in that country as such, or by a copy`
  line `certified under the seal of the country or sovereign, or by a recognition thereof in any Central Act;`
  line
  line `(e) the proceedings of a municipal or local body in a State, by a copy of such proceedings,`
  line `certified by the legal keeper thereof, or by a printed book purporting to be published by the authority`
  line `of such body;`
  line
  line `(f) public documents of any other class in a foreign country, by the original or by a copy certified`
  line `by the legal keeper thereof, with a certificate under the seal of a Notary Public, or of an Indian`
  line `Consul or diplomatic agent, that the copy is duly certified by the officer having the legal custody of`
  line `the original, and upon proof of the character of the document according to the law of the foreign`
  line country.
obj_root_law_sections_77_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_78:
  sectionId (90845)
  sectionNo (78)
  orderNo 78
  title `Presumption as to genuineness of certified copies.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_78_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_78_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90845&sectionno=78&orderno=78&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_78_content:
  string
  line `(1) The Court shall presume to be genuine`
  line `every document purporting to be a certificate, certified copy or other document, which is by law declared`
  line `to be admissible as evidence of any particular fact and which purports to be duly certified by any officer`
  line `of the Central Government or of a State Government:`
  line
  line `Provided that such document is substantially in the form and purports to be executed in the manner`
  line `directed by law in that behalf.`
  line
  line `(2) The Court shall also presume that any officer by whom any such document purports to be signed`
  line `or certified, held, when he signed it, the official character which he claims in such paper.`
obj_root_law_sections_78_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_79:
  sectionId (90846)
  sectionNo (79)
  orderNo 79
  title `Presumption as to documents produced as record of evidence, etc.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_79_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_79_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90846&sectionno=79&orderno=79&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_79_content:
  string
  line `Whenever any document`
  line `is produced before any Court, purporting to be a record or memorandum of the evidence, or of any part of`
  line `the evidence, given by a witness in a judicial proceeding or before any officer authorised by law to take`
  line `such evidence or to be a statement or confession by any prisoner or accused person, taken in accordance`
  line `with law, and purporting to be signed by any Judge or Magistrate, or by any such officer as aforesaid, the`
  line `Court shall presume that--`
  line
  line `(i) the document is genuine;`
  line
  line `(ii) any statements as to the circumstances under which it was taken, purporting to be made by`
  line `the person signing it, are true; and`
  line
  line `(iii) such evidence, statement or confession was duly taken.`
obj_root_law_sections_79_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_80:
  sectionId (90847)
  sectionNo (80)
  orderNo 80
  title `Presumption as to Gazettes, newspapers, and other documents.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_80_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_80_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90847&sectionno=80&orderno=80&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_80_content:
  string
  line `The Court shall presume the`
  line `genuineness of every document purporting to be the Official Gazette, or to be a newspaper or journal, and`
  line `of every document purporting to be a document directed by any law to be kept by any person, if such`
  line `document is kept substantially in the form required by law and is produced from proper custody.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--For the purposes of this section and section 92, document is said to be in proper`
  line `custody if it is in the place in which, and looked after by the person with whom such document is`
  line `required to be kept; but no custody is improper if it is proved to have had a legitimate origin, or if the`
  line `circumstances of the particular case are such as to render that origin probable.`
obj_root_law_sections_80_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_81:
  sectionId (90848)
  sectionNo (81)
  orderNo 81
  title `Presumption as to Gazettes in electronic or digital record.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_81_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_81_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90848&sectionno=81&orderno=81&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_81_content:
  string
  line `The Court shall presume the`
  line `genuineness of every electronic or digital record purporting to be the Official Gazette, or purporting to be`
  line `electronic or digital record directed by any law to be kept by any person, if such electronic or digital`
  line `record is kept substantially in the form required by law and is produced from proper custody.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--For the purposes of this section and section 93 electronic records are said to be in`
  line `proper custody if they are in the place in which, and looked after by the person with whom such`
  line `document is required to be kept; but no custody is improper if it is proved to have had a legitimate origin,`
  line `or the circumstances of the particular case are such as to render that origin probable.`
obj_root_law_sections_81_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_82:
  sectionId (90849)
  sectionNo (82)
  orderNo 82
  title `Presumption as to maps or plans made by authority of Government.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_82_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_82_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90849&sectionno=82&orderno=82&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_82_content:
  string
  line `The Court shall`
  line `presume that maps or plans purporting to be made by the authority of the Central Government or any`
  line `State Government were so made, and are accurate; but maps or plans made for the purposes of any cause`
  line `must be proved to be accurate.`
obj_root_law_sections_82_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_83:
  sectionId (90850)
  sectionNo (83)
  orderNo 83
  title `Presumption as to collections of laws and reports of decisions.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_83_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_83_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90850&sectionno=83&orderno=83&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_83_content:
  string
  line `The Court shall presume the`
  line `genuineness of, every book purporting to be printed or published under the authority of the Government`
  line `of any country, and to contain any of the laws of that country, and of every book purporting to contain`
  line `reports of decisions of the Courts of such country`
obj_root_law_sections_83_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_84:
  sectionId (90851)
  sectionNo (84)
  orderNo 84
  title `Presumption as to powers-of-attorney.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_84_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_84_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90851&sectionno=84&orderno=84&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_84_content:
  string
  line `The Court shall presume that every document`
  line `purporting to be a power-of-attorney, and to have been executed before, and authenticated by, a Notary`
  line `Public, or any Court, Judge, Magistrate, Indian Consul or Vice-Consul, or representative of the Central`
  line `Government, was so executed and authenticated.`
obj_root_law_sections_84_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_85:
  sectionId (90852)
  sectionNo (85)
  orderNo 85
  title `Presumption as to electronic agreements.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_85_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_85_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90852&sectionno=85&orderno=85&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_85_content:
  string
  line `The Court shall presume that every electronic`
  line `record purporting to be an agreement containing the electronic or digital signature of the parties was so`
  line `concluded by affixing the electronic or digital signature of the parties.`
obj_root_law_sections_85_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_86:
  sectionId (90853)
  sectionNo (86)
  orderNo 86
  title `Presumption as to electronic records and electronic signatures.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_86_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_86_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90853&sectionno=86&orderno=86&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_86_content:
  string
  line `(1) In any proceeding`
  line `involving a secure electronic record, the Court shall presume unless contrary is proved, that the secure`
  line `electronic record has not been altered since the specific point of time to which the secure status relates.`
  line
  line `(2) In any proceeding, involving secure electronic signature, the Court shall presume unless the`
  line `contrary is proved that--`
  line
  line `(a) the secure electronic signature is affixed by subscriber with the intention of signing or`
  line `approving the electronic record;`
  line
  line `(b) except in the case of a secure electronic record or a secure electronic signature, nothing in this`
  line `section shall create any presumption, relating to authenticity and integrity of the electronic record or`
  line `any electronic signature.`
obj_root_law_sections_86_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_87:
  sectionId (90854)
  sectionNo (87)
  orderNo 87
  title `Presumption as to Electronic Signature Certificates.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_87_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_87_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90854&sectionno=87&orderno=87&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_87_content:
  string
  line `The Court shall presume, unless`
  line `contrary is proved, that the information listed in an Electronic Signature Certificate is correct, except for`
  line `information specified as subscriber information which has not been verified, if the certificate was`
  line `accepted by the subscriber.`
obj_root_law_sections_87_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_88:
  sectionId (90855)
  sectionNo (88)
  orderNo 88
  title `Presumption as to certified copies of foreign judicial records.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_88_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_88_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90855&sectionno=88&orderno=88&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_88_content:
  string
  line `(1) The Court may presume`
  line `that any document purporting to be a certified copy of any judicial record of any country beyond India is`
  line `genuine and accurate, if the document purports to be certified in any manner which is certified by any`
  line `representative of the Central Government in or for such country to be the manner commonly in use in that`
  line `country for the certification of copies of judicial records.`
  line
  line `(2) An officer who, with respect to any territory or place outside India is a Political Agent therefor, as`
  line `defined in clause (43) of section 3 of the General Clauses Act, 1897 (10 of 1897), shall, for the purposes`
  line `of this section, be deemed to be a representative of the Central Government in and for the country`
  line `comprising that territory or place.`
obj_root_law_sections_88_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_89:
  sectionId (90856)
  sectionNo (89)
  orderNo 89
  title `Presumption as to books, maps and charts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_89_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_89_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90856&sectionno=89&orderno=89&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_89_content:
  string
  line `The Court may presume that any book to which it`
  line `may refer for information on matters of public or general interest, and that any published map or chart,`
  line `the statements of which are relevant facts, and which is produced for its inspection, was written and published by the person, and at the time and place, by whom or at which it purports to have been written`
  line `or published.`
obj_root_law_sections_89_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_90:
  sectionId (90857)
  sectionNo (90)
  orderNo 90
  title `Presumption as to electronic messages.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_90_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_90_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90857&sectionno=90&orderno=90&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_90_content:
  string
  line `The Court may presume that an electronic message,`
  line `forwarded by the originator through an electronic mail server to the addressee to whom the message`
  line `purports to be addressed corresponds with the message as fed into his computer for transmission; but the`
  line `Court shall not make any presumption as to the person by whom such message was sent.`
obj_root_law_sections_90_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_91:
  sectionId (90858)
  sectionNo (91)
  orderNo 91
  title `Presumption as to due execution, etc., of documents not produced.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_91_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_91_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90858&sectionno=91&orderno=91&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_91_content:
  string
  line `The Court shall presume`
  line `that every document, called for and not produced after notice to produce, was attested, stamped and`
  line `executed in the manner required by law.`
obj_root_law_sections_91_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_92:
  sectionId (90859)
  sectionNo (92)
  orderNo 92
  title `Presumption as to documents thirty years old.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_92_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_92_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90859&sectionno=92&orderno=92&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_92_content:
  string
  line `Where any document, purporting or proved to`
  line `be thirty years old, is produced from any custody which the Court in the particular case considers proper,`
  line `the Court may presume that the signature and every other part of such document, which purports to be in`
  line `the handwriting of any particular person, is in that person’s handwriting, and, in the case of a document`
  line `executed or attested, that it was duly executed and attested by the persons by whom it purports to be`
  line `executed and attested.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--The Explanation to section 80 shall also apply to this section.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A has been in possession of landed property for a long time. He produces from his custody deeds`
  line `relating to the land showing his titles to it. The custody shall be proper.`
  line
  line `(b) A produces deeds relating to landed property of which he is the mortgagee. The mortgagor is in`
  line `possession. The custody shall be proper.`
  line
  line `(c) A, a connection of B, produces deeds relating to lands in B's possession, which were deposited`
  line `with him by B for safe custody. The custody shall be proper.`
obj_root_law_sections_92_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_93:
  sectionId (90860)
  sectionNo (93)
  orderNo 93
  title `Presumption as to electronic records five years old.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_93_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_93_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90860&sectionno=93&orderno=93&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_93_content:
  string
  line `Where any electronic record, purporting`
  line `or proved to be five years old, is produced from any custody which the Court in the particular case`
  line `considers proper, the Court may presume that the electronic signature which purports to be the electronic`
  line `signature of any particular person was so affixed by him or any person authorised by him in this behalf.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--The Explanation to section 81 shall also apply to this section.`
obj_root_law_sections_93_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_94:
  sectionId (90946)
  sectionNo (94)
  orderNo 94
  title `Evidence of terms of contracts, grants and other dispositions of property reduced to form of document.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_94_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_94_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90946&sectionno=94&orderno=94&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_94_content:
  string
  line `When the terms of a contract, or of a grant, or of any other disposition of property, have`
  line `been reduced to the form of a document, and in all cases in which any matter is required by law to be`
  line `reduced to the form of a document, no evidence shall be given in proof of the terms of such contract,`
  line `grant or other disposition of property, or of such matter, except the document itself, or secondary`
  line `evidence of its contents in cases in which secondary evidence is admissible under the provisions`
  line `hereinbefore contained`
  line
  line `Exception 1.--When a public officer is required by law to be appointed in writing, and when it is shown that any particular person has acted as such officer, the writing by which he is appointed need not be proved.`
  line
  line `Exception 2.--Wills admitted to probate in India may be proved by the probate.`
  line
  line `Explanation 1.--This section applies equally to cases in which the contracts, grants or dispositions of`
  line `property referred to are contained in one document, and to cases in which they are contained in more`
  line `documents than one.`
  line
  line `Explanation 2.--Where there are more originals than one, one original only need be proved.`
  line
  line `Explanation 3.--The statement, in any document whatever, of a fact other than the facts referred to in this section, shall not preclude the admission of oral evidence as to the same fact.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) If a contract be contained in several letters, all the letters in which it is contained must be proved.`
  line
  line `(b) If a contract is contained in a bill of exchange, the bill of exchange must be proved.`
  line
  line `(d) A contracts, in writing, with B, for the delivery of indigo upon certain terms. The contract`
  line `mentions the fact that B had paid A the price of other indigo contracted for verbally on another occasion.`
  line `Oral evidence is offered that no payment was made for the other indigo. The evidence is admissible.`
  line
  line `(e) A gives B a receipt for money paid by B. Oral evidence is offered of the payment. The evidence is`
  line admissible
obj_root_law_sections_94_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_95:
  sectionId (90862)
  sectionNo (95)
  orderNo 95
  title `Exclusion of evidence of oral agreement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_95_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_95_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90862&sectionno=95&orderno=95&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_95_content:
  string
  line `When the terms of any such contract, grant or other`
  line `disposition of property, or any matter required by law to be reduced to the form of a document, have been`
  line `proved according to section 94, no evidence of any oral agreement or statement shall be admitted, as`
  line `between the parties to any such instrument or their representatives in interest, for the purpose of`
  line `contradicting, varying, adding to, or subtracting from, its terms:`
  line
  line `Provided that any fact may be proved which would invalidate any document, or which would entitle`
  line `any person to any decree or order relating thereto; such as fraud, intimidation, illegality, want of due`
  line `execution, want of capacity in any contracting party, want or failure of consideration, or mistake in fact`
  line `or law:`
  line
  line `Provided further that the existence of any separate oral agreement as to any matter on which a`
  line `document is silent, and which is not inconsistent with its terms, may be proved. In considering whether or`
  line `not this proviso applies, the Court shall have regard to the degree of formality of the document:`
  line
  line `Provided also that the existence of any separate oral agreement, constituting a condition precedent to`
  line `the attaching of any obligation under any such contract, grant or disposition of property, may be proved:`
  line
  line `Provided also that the existence of any distinct subsequent oral agreement to rescind or modify any`
  line `such contract, grant or disposition of property, may be proved, except in cases in which such contract,`
  line `grant or disposition of property is by law required to be in writing, or has been registered according to the`
  line `law in force for the time being as to the registration of documents:`
  line
  line `Provided also that any usage or custom by which incidents not expressly mentioned in any contract`
  line `are usually annexed to contracts of that description, may be proved:`
  line
  line `Provided also that the annexing of such incident would not be repugnant to, or inconsistent with, the`
  line `express terms of the contract:`
  line
  line `Provided also that any fact may be proved which shows in what manner the language of a document`
  line `is related to existing facts.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A policy of insurance is effected on goods "in ships from Kolkata to Visakhapatnam". The goods`
  line `are shipped in a particular ship which is lost. The fact that particular ship was orally excepted from the`
  line `policy, cannot be proved.`
  line
  line `(b) A agrees absolutely in writing to pay B one thousand rupees on the 1st March, 2023. The fact`
  line `that, at the same time, an oral agreement was made that the money should not be paid till the 31st March,`
  line `2023, cannot be proved.`
  line
  line `(c) An estate called "the Rampur tea estate" is sold by a deed which contains a map of the property sold. The fact that land not included in the map had always been regarded as part of the estate and was meant to pass by the deed cannot be proved.`
  line
  line `(d) A enters into a written contract with B to work certain mines, the property of B, upon certain`
  line `terms. A was induced to do so by a misrepresentation of B's as to their value. This fact may be proved.`
  line
  line `(e) A institutes a suit against B for the specific performance of a contract, and also prays that the`
  line `contract may be reformed as to one of its provisions, as that provision was inserted in it by mistake. A`
  line `may prove that such a mistake was made as would by law entitle him to have the contract reformed.`
  line
  line `(f) A orders goods of B by a letter in which nothing is said as to the time of payment, and accepts the`
  line `goods on delivery. B sues A for the price. A may show that the goods were supplied on credit for a term`
  line `still unexpired.`
  line
  line `(g) A sells B a horse and verbally warrants him sound. A gives B a paper in these words-- "Bought of A a horse for thirty thousand rupees". B may prove the verbal warranty`
  line
  line `(h) A hires lodgings of B, and gives B a card on which is written-- "Rooms, ten thousand rupees a month". A may prove a verbal agreement that these terms were to include partial board. A hires lodging of B for a year, and a regularly stamped agreement, drawn up by an advocate, is made between them. It is silent on the subject of board. A may not prove that board was included in the term verbally.`
  line
  line `(i) A applies to B for a debt due to A by sending a receipt for the money. B keeps the receipt and does not send the money. In a suit for the amount, A may prove this.`
  line
  line `(j) A and B make a contract in writing to take effect upon the happening of a certain contingency.`
  line `The writing is left with B who sues A upon it. A may show the circumstances under which it was`
  line delivered.
obj_root_law_sections_95_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_96:
  sectionId (90863)
  sectionNo (96)
  orderNo 96
  title `Exclusion of evidence to explain or amend ambiguous document.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_96_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_96_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90863&sectionno=96&orderno=96&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_96_content:
  string
  line `When the language used`
  line `in a document is, on its face, ambiguous or defective, evidence may not be given of facts which would`
  line `show its meaning or supply its defects.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A agrees, in writing, to sell a horse to B for "one lakh rupees or one lakh fifty thousand rupees". Evidence cannot be given to show which price was to be given.`
  line
  line `(b) A deed contains blanks. Evidence cannot be given of facts which would show how they were`
  line `meant to be filled.`
obj_root_law_sections_96_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_97:
  sectionId (90864)
  sectionNo (97)
  orderNo 97
  title `Exclusion of evidence against application of document to existing facts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_97_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_97_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90864&sectionno=97&orderno=97&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_97_content:
  string
  line `When language`
  line `used in a document is plain in itself, and when it applies accurately to existing facts, evidence may not be`
  line `given to show that it was not meant to apply to such facts.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A sells to B, by deed, “my estate at Rampur containing one hundred bighas”. A has an estate at`
  line `Rampur containing one hundred bighas. Evidence may not be given of the fact that the estate meant to be`
  line `sold was one situated at a different place and of a different size.`
obj_root_law_sections_97_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_98:
  sectionId (90865)
  sectionNo (98)
  orderNo 98
  title `Evidence as to document unmeaning in reference to existing facts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_98_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_98_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90865&sectionno=98&orderno=98&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_98_content:
  string
  line `When language used in a`
  line `document is plain in itself, but is unmeaning in reference to existing facts, evidence may be given to`
  line `show that it was used in a peculiar sense.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A sells to B, by deed, “my house in Kolkata”. A had no house in Kolkata, but it appears that he had a`
  line `house at Howrah, of which B had been in possession since the execution of the deed. These facts may be`
  line `proved to show that the deed related to the house at Howrah.`
obj_root_law_sections_98_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_99:
  sectionId (90866)
  sectionNo (99)
  orderNo 99
  title `Evidence as to application of language which can apply to one only of several persons.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_99_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_99_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90866&sectionno=99&orderno=99&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_99_content:
  string
  line `When the facts are such that the language used might have been meant to apply to any one, and could not`
  line `have been meant to apply to more than one, of several persons or things, evidence may be given of facts`
  line `which show which of those persons or things it was intended to apply to.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A agrees to sell to B, for one thousand rupees, "my white horse". A has two white horses.`
  line `Evidence may be given of facts which show which of them was meant`
  line
  line `(b) A agrees to accompany B to Ramgarh. Evidence may be given of facts showing whether Ramgarh`
  line `in Rajasthan or Ramgarh in Uttarakhand was meant.`
obj_root_law_sections_99_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_100:
  sectionId (90947)
  sectionNo (100)
  orderNo 100
  title `. Evidence as to application of language to one of two sets of facts, to neither of which the whole correctly applies.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_100_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_100_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90947&sectionno=100&orderno=100&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_100_content:
  string
  line `When the language used applies partly to one set of existing facts, and partly`
  line `to another set of existing facts, but the whole of it does not apply correctly to either, evidence may be`
  line `given to show to which of the two it was meant to apply.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A agrees to sell to B "my land at X in the occupation of Y". A has land at X, but not in the`
  line `occupation of Y, and he has land in the occupation of Y but it is not at X. Evidence may be given of facts`
  line `showing which he meant to sell.`
obj_root_law_sections_100_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_101:
  sectionId (90868)
  sectionNo (101)
  orderNo 101
  title `Evidence as to meaning of illegible characters, etc.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_101_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_101_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90868&sectionno=101&orderno=101&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_101_content:
  string
  line `Evidence may be given to show the`
  line `meaning of illegible or not commonly intelligible characters, of foreign, obsolete, technical, local and`
  line `regional expressions, of abbreviations and of words used in a peculiar sense.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A, sculptor, agrees to sell to B, "all my mods". A has both models and modelling tools. Evidence`
  line `may be given to show which he meant to sell.`
obj_root_law_sections_101_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_102:
  sectionId (90869)
  sectionNo (102)
  orderNo 102
  title `Who may give evidence of agreement varying terms of document.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_102_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_102_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90869&sectionno=102&orderno=102&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_102_content:
  string
  line `Persons who are not`
  line `parties to a document, or their representatives in interest, may give evidence of any facts tending to show`
  line `a contemporaneous agreement varying the terms of the document.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A and B make a contract in writing that B shall sell A certain cotton, to be paid for on delivery. At`
  line `the same time, they make an oral agreement that three months’ credit shall be given to A. This could not`
  line `be shown as between A and B, but it might be shown by C, if it affected his interests.`
obj_root_law_sections_102_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_103:
  sectionId (90870)
  sectionNo (103)
  orderNo 103
  title `Saving of provisions of Indian Succession Act relating to wills.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_103_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_103_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90870&sectionno=103&orderno=103&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_103_content:
  string
  line `Nothing in this Chapter`
  line `shall be taken to affect any of the provisions of the Indian Succession Act, 1925 (39 of 1925) as to the`
  line `construction of wills.`
obj_root_law_sections_103_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_104:
  sectionId (90871)
  sectionNo (104)
  orderNo 104
  title `Burden of proof.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_104_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_104_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90871&sectionno=104&orderno=104&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_104_content:
  string
  line `Whoever desires any Court to give judgment as to any legal right or liability`
  line `dependent on the existence of facts which he asserts must prove that those facts exist, and when a person`
  line `is bound to prove the existence of any fact, it is said that the burden of proof lies on that person.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A desires a Court to give judgment that B shall be punished for a crime which A says B has`
  line `committed. A must prove that B has committed the crime.`
  line
  line `(b) A desires a Court to give judgment that he is entitled to certain land in the possession of B, by`
  line `reason of facts which he asserts, and which B denies, to be true. A must prove the existence of those`
  line facts.
obj_root_law_sections_104_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_105:
  sectionId (90872)
  sectionNo (105)
  orderNo 105
  title `On whom burden of proof lies.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_105_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_105_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90872&sectionno=105&orderno=105&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_105_content:
  string
  line `The burden of proof in a suit or proceeding lies on that`
  line `person who would fail if no evidence at all were given on either side`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A sues B for land of which B is in possession, and which, as A asserts, was left to A by the will of`
  line `C, B's father. If no evidence were given on either side, B would be entitled to retain his possession.`
  line `Therefore, the burden of proof is on A.`
  line
  line `(b) A sues B for money due on a bond. The execution of the bond is admitted, but B says that it was`
  line `obtained by fraud, which A denies. If no evidence were given on either side, A would succeed, as the`
  line `bond is not disputed and the fraud is not proved. Therefore, the burden of proof is on B.`
obj_root_law_sections_105_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_106:
  sectionId (90873)
  sectionNo (106)
  orderNo 106
  title `Burden of proof as to particular fact.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_106_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_106_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90873&sectionno=106&orderno=106&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_106_content:
  string
  line `The burden of proof as to any particular fact lies on`
  line `that person who wishes the Court to believe in its existence, unless it is provided by any law that the`
  line `proof of that fact shall lie on any particular person.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A prosecutes B for theft, and wishes the Court to believe that B admitted the theft to C. A must prove`
  line `the admission. B wishes the Court to believe that, at the time in question, he was elsewhere. He must`
  line `prove it.`
obj_root_law_sections_106_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_107:
  sectionId (90874)
  sectionNo (107)
  orderNo 107
  title `Burden of proving fact to be proved to make evidence admissible.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_107_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_107_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90874&sectionno=107&orderno=107&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_107_content:
  string
  line `The burden of proving`
  line `any fact necessary to be proved in order to enable any person to give evidence of any other fact is on the`
  line `person who wishes to give such evidence`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A wishes to prove a dying declaration by B. A must prove B's death.`
  line
  line `(b) A wishes to prove, by secondary evidence, the contents of a lost document. A must prove that the`
  line `document has been lost.`
obj_root_law_sections_107_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_108:
  sectionId (90875)
  sectionNo (108)
  orderNo 108
  title `Burden of proving that case of accused comes within exceptions.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_108_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_108_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90875&sectionno=108&orderno=108&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_108_content:
  string
  line `When a person is accused`
  line `of any offence, the burden of proving the existence of circumstances bringing the case within any of the`
  line `General Exceptions in the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023 or within any special exception or proviso`
  line `contained in any other part of the said Sanhita, or in any law defining the offence, is upon him, and the`
  line `Court shall presume the absence of such circumstances.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A, accused of murder, alleges that, by reason of unsoundness of mind, he did not know the nature`
  line `of the act. The burden of proof is on A.`
  line
  line `(b) A, accused of murder, alleges that, by grave and sudden provocation, he was deprived of the`
  line `power of self-control. The burden of proof is on A.`
  line
  line `(c) Section 117 of the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023 provides that whoever, except in the case`
  line `provided for by sub-section (2) of section 122, voluntarily causes grievous hurt, shall be subject to certain`
  line `punishments. A is charged with voluntarily causing grievous hurt under section 117. The burden of`
  line `proving the circumstances bringing the case under sub-section (2) of section 122 lies on A.`
obj_root_law_sections_108_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_109:
  sectionId (90876)
  sectionNo (109)
  orderNo 109
  title `Burden of proving fact especially within knowledge.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_109_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_109_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90876&sectionno=109&orderno=109&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_109_content:
  string
  line `When any fact is especially within the`
  line `knowledge of any person, the burden of proving that fact is upon him.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) When a person does an act with some intention other than that which the character and`
  line `circumstances of the act suggest, the burden of proving that intention is upon him.`
  line
  line `(b) A is charged with travelling on a railway without a ticket. The burden of proving that he had a`
  line `ticket is on him.`
obj_root_law_sections_109_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_110:
  sectionId (90877)
  sectionNo (110)
  orderNo 110
  title `Burden of proving death of person known to have been alive within thirty years.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_110_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_110_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90877&sectionno=110&orderno=110&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_110_content:
  string
  line When
  line `the question is whether a man is alive or dead, and it is shown that he was alive within thirty years, the`
  line `burden of proving that he is dead is on the person who affirms it.`
obj_root_law_sections_110_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_111:
  sectionId (90878)
  sectionNo (111)
  orderNo 111
  title `Burden of proving that person is alive who has not been heard of for seven years.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_111_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_111_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90878&sectionno=111&orderno=111&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_111_content:
  string
  line When
  line `the question is whether a man is alive or dead, and it is proved that he has not been heard of for seven`
  line `years by those who would naturally have heard of him if he had been alive, the burden of proving that he`
  line `is alive is shifted to the person who affirms it.`
obj_root_law_sections_111_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_112:
  sectionId (90948)
  sectionNo (112)
  orderNo 112
  title `Burden of proof as to relationship in the cases of partners, landlord and tenant, principal and agent.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_112_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_112_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90948&sectionno=112&orderno=112&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_112_content:
  string
  line `When the question is whether persons are partners, landlord and tenant, or principal and`
  line `agent, and it has been shown that they have been acting as such, the burden of proving that they do not`
  line `stand, or have ceased to stand, to each other in those relationships respectively, is on the person who`
  line `affirms it`
obj_root_law_sections_112_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_113:
  sectionId (90880)
  sectionNo (113)
  orderNo 113
  title `Burden of proof as to ownership.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_113_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_113_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90880&sectionno=113&orderno=113&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_113_content:
  string
  line `When the question is whether any person is owner of`
  line `anything of which he is shown to be in possession, the burden of proving that he is not the owner is on`
  line `the person who affirms that he is not the owner.`
obj_root_law_sections_113_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_114:
  sectionId (90881)
  sectionNo (114)
  orderNo 114
  title `Proof of good faith in transactions where one party is in relation of active confidence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_114_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_114_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90881&sectionno=114&orderno=114&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_114_content:
  string
  line `Where there is a question as to the good faith of a transaction between parties, one of whom stands to the`
  line `other in a position of active confidence, the burden of proving the good faith of the transaction is on the`
  line `party who is in a position of active confidence.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) The good faith of a sale by a client to an advocate is in question in a suit brought by the client.`
  line `The burden of proving the good faith of the transaction is on the advocate.`
  line
  line `(b) The good faith of a sale by a son just come of age to a father is in question in a suit brought by the`
  line `son. The burden of proving the good faith of the transaction is on the father`
obj_root_law_sections_114_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_115:
  sectionId (90882)
  sectionNo (115)
  orderNo 115
  title `Presumption as to certain offences.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_115_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_115_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90882&sectionno=115&orderno=115&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_115_content:
  string
  line `(1) Where a person is accused of having committed any`
  line `offence specified in sub-section (2), in--`
  line
  line `(a) any area declared to be a disturbed area under any enactment for the time being in force,`
  line `making provision for the suppression of disorder and restoration and maintenance of public order; or`
  line
  line `(b) any area in which there has been, over a period of more than one month, extensive`
  line `disturbance of the public peace,`
  line
  line `and it is shown that such person had been at a place in such area at a time when firearms or explosives`
  line `were used at or from that place to attack or resist the members of any armed forces or the forces charged`
  line `with the maintenance of public order acting in the discharge of their duties, it shall be presumed, unless`
  line `the contrary is shown, that such person had committed such offence.`
  line
  line `(2) The offences referred to in sub-section (1) are the following, namely:--`
  line
  line `(a) an offence under section 147, section 148, section 149 or section 150 of the Bharatiya Nyaya`
  line `Sanhita, 2023;`
  line
  line `(b) criminal conspiracy or attempt to commit, or abetment of, an offence under section 149 or section 150 of the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023.`
obj_root_law_sections_115_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_116:
  sectionId (90883)
  sectionNo (116)
  orderNo 116
  title `Birth during marriage, conclusive proof of legitimacy.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_116_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_116_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90883&sectionno=116&orderno=116&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_116_content:
  string
  line `The fact that any person was born`
  line `during the continuance of a valid marriage between his mother and any man, or within two hundred and`
  line `eighty days after its dissolution, the mother remaining unmarried, shall be conclusive proof that he is the`
  line `legitimate child of that man, unless it can be shown that the parties to the marriage had no access to each`
  line `other at any time when he could have been begotten.`
obj_root_law_sections_116_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_117:
  sectionId (90884)
  sectionNo (117)
  orderNo 117
  title `Presumption as to abetment of suicide by a married woman.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_117_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_117_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90884&sectionno=117&orderno=117&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_117_content:
  string
  line `When the question is whether`
  line `the commission of suicide by a woman had been abetted by her husband or any relative of her husband`
  line `and it is shown that she had committed suicide within a period of seven years from the date of her`
  line `marriage and that her husband or such relative of her husband had subjected her to cruelty, the Court may presume, having regard to all the other circumstances of the case, that such suicide had been abetted by`
  line `her husband or by such relative of her husband.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--For the purposes of this section, "cruelty" shall have the same meaning as in section 86 of the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023.`
obj_root_law_sections_117_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_118:
  sectionId (90885)
  sectionNo (118)
  orderNo 118
  title `Presumption as to dowry death.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_118_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_118_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90885&sectionno=118&orderno=118&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_118_content:
  string
  line `When the question is whether a person has committed the`
  line `dowry death of a woman and it is shown that soon before her death, such woman had been subjected by`
  line `such person to cruelty or harassment for, or in connection with, any demand for dowry, the Court shall`
  line `presume that such person had caused the dowry death.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--For the purposes of this section, "dowry death" shall have the same meaning as in section 80 of the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023.`
obj_root_law_sections_118_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_119:
  sectionId (90886)
  sectionNo (119)
  orderNo 119
  title `Court may presume existence of certain facts.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_119_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_119_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90886&sectionno=119&orderno=119&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_119_content:
  string
  line `(1) The Court may presume the existence of`
  line `any fact which it thinks likely to have happened, regard being had to the common course of natural`
  line `events, human conduct and public and private business, in their relation to the facts of the particular case.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `The Court may presume that--`
  line
  line `(a) a man who is in possession of stolen goods soon, after the theft is either the thief or has`
  line `received the goods knowing them to be stolen, unless he can account for his possession;`
  line
  line `(a) a man who is in possession of stolen goods soon, after the theft is either the thief or has`
  line `received the goods knowing them to be stolen, unless he can account for his possession;`
  line
  line `(b) an accomplice is unworthy of credit, unless he is corroborated in material particulars;`
  line
  line `(c) a bill of exchange, accepted or endorsed, was accepted or endorsed for good consideration;`
  line
  line `(d) a thing or state of things which has been shown to be in existence within a period shorter than`
  line `that within which such things or state of things usually cease to exist, is still in existence;`
  line
  line `(e) judicial and official acts have been regularly performed;`
  line
  line `(f) the common course of business has been followed in particular cases;`
  line
  line `(g) evidence which could be and is not produced would, if produced, be unfavourable to the`
  line `person who withholds it;`
  line
  line `(h) if a man refuses to answer a question which he is not compelled to answer by law, the answer,`
  line `if given, would be unfavourable to him;`
  line
  line `(i) when a document creating an obligation is in the hands of the obligor, the obligation has been`
  line discharged.
  line
  line `(2) The Court shall also have regard to such facts as the following, in considering whether such`
  line `maxims do or do not apply to the particular case before it:--`
  line
  line `(i) as to Illustration (a)--a shop-keeper has in his bill a marked rupee soon after it was stolen,`
  line `and cannot account for its possession specifically, but is continually receiving rupees in the course of`
  line `his business;`
  line
  line `(ii) as to Illustration (b) --A, a person of the highest character, is tried for causing a man's death`
  line `by an act of negligence in arranging certain machinery. B, a person of equally good character, who`
  line `also took part in the arrangement, describes precisely what was done, and admits and explains the`
  line `common carelessness of A and himself;`
  line
  line `(iii) as to Illustration (b) --a crime is committed by several persons. A, B and C, three of the`
  line `criminals, are captured on the spot and kept apart from each other. Each gives an account of the crime`
  line `implicating D, and the accounts corroborate each other in such a manner as to render previous`
  line `concert highly improbable;`
  line
  line `(iv) as to Illustration (c)--A, the drawer of a bill of exchange, was a man of business. B, the`
  line `acceptor, was a young and ignorant person, completely under A's influence;`
  line
  line `(v) as to Illustration (d)--it is proved that a river ran in a certain course five years ago, but it is`
  line `known that there have been floods since that time which might change its course;`
  line
  line `(vi) as to Illustration (e)--a judicial act, the regularity of which is in question, was performed`
  line `under exceptional circumstances;`
  line
  line `(vii) as to Illustration (f)--the question is, whether a letter was received. It is shown to have been`
  line `posted, but the usual course of the post was interrupted by disturbances;`
  line
  line `(viii) as to Illustration (g)--a man refuses to produce a document which would bear on a contract`
  line `of small importance on which he is sued, but which might also injure the feelings and reputation of`
  line `his family;`
  line
  line `(ix) as to Illustration (h)--a man refuses to answer a question which he is not compelled by law`
  line `to answer, but the answer to it might cause loss to him in matters unconnected with the matter in`
  line `relation to which it is asked;`
  line
  line `(x) as to Illustration (i)--a bond is in possession of the obligor, but the circumstances of the case`
  line `are such that he may have stolen it.`
obj_root_law_sections_119_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_120:
  sectionId (90887)
  sectionNo (120)
  orderNo 120
  title `Presumption as to absence of consent in certain prosecution for rape.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_120_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_120_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90887&sectionno=120&orderno=120&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_120_content:
  string
  line `In a prosecution for`
  line `rape under sub-section (2) of section 64 of the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023, where sexual intercourse`
  line `by the accused is proved and the question is whether it was without the consent of the woman alleged to`
  line `have been raped and such woman states in her evidence before the Court that she did not consent, the`
  line `Court shall presume that she did not consent.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--In this section, "sexual intercourse" shall mean any of the acts mentioned in`
  line `section 63 of the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023.`
obj_root_law_sections_120_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_121:
  sectionId (90888)
  sectionNo (121)
  orderNo 121
  title Estoppel.
  content obj_root_law_sections_121_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_121_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90888&sectionno=121&orderno=121&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_121_content:
  string
  line `When one person has, by his declaration, act or omission, intentionally caused or`
  line `permitted another person to believe a thing to be true and to act upon such belief, neither he nor his`
  line `representative shall be allowed, in any suit or proceeding between himself and such person or his`
  line `representative, to deny the truth of that thing.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `A intentionally and falsely leads B to believe that certain land belongs to A, and thereby induces B to`
  line `buy and pay for it. The land afterwards becomes the property of A, and A seeks to set aside the sale on`
  line `the ground that, at the time of the sale, he had no title. He must not be allowed to prove his want of title`
obj_root_law_sections_121_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_122:
  sectionId (90889)
  sectionNo (122)
  orderNo 122
  title `Estoppel of tenant and of licensee of person in possession.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_122_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_122_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90889&sectionno=122&orderno=122&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_122_content:
  string
  line `No tenant of immovable`
  line `property, or person claiming through such tenant, shall, during the continuance of the tenancy or any time`
  line `thereafter, be permitted to deny that the landlord of such tenant had, at the beginning of the tenancy, a`
  line `title to such immovable property; and no person who came upon any immovable property by the licence`
  line `of the person in possession thereof shall be permitted to deny that such person had a title to such`
  line `possession at the time when such licence was given.`
obj_root_law_sections_122_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_123:
  sectionId (90890)
  sectionNo (123)
  orderNo 123
  title `Estoppel of acceptor of bill of exchange, bailee or licensee.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_123_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_123_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90890&sectionno=123&orderno=123&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_123_content:
  string
  line `No acceptor of a bill of`
  line `exchange shall be permitted to deny that the drawer had authority to draw such bill or to endorse it; nor`
  line `shall any bailee or licensee be permitted to deny that his bailor or licensor had, at the time when the`
  line `bailment or licence commenced, authority to make such bailment or grant such licence.`
  line
  line `Explanation 1.--The acceptor of a bill of exchange may deny that the bill was really drawn by the`
  line `person by whom it purports to have been drawn.`
  line
  line `Explanation 2.--If a bailee delivers the goods bailed to a person other than the bailor, he may prove`
  line `that such person had a right to them as against the bailor.`
obj_root_law_sections_123_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_124:
  sectionId (90891)
  sectionNo (124)
  orderNo 124
  title `Who may testify.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_124_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_124_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90891&sectionno=124&orderno=124&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_124_content:
  string
  line `All persons shall be competent to testify unless the Court considers that`
  line `they are prevented from understanding the questions put to them, or from giving rational answers to those`
  line `questions, by tender years, extreme old age, disease, whether of body or mind, or any other cause of the`
  line `same kind.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--A person of unsound mind is not incompetent to testify, unless he is prevented by his`
  line `unsoundness of mind from understanding the questions put to him and giving rational answers to them.`
obj_root_law_sections_124_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_125:
  sectionId (90892)
  sectionNo (125)
  orderNo 125
  title `Witness unable to communicate verbally.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_125_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_125_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90892&sectionno=125&orderno=125&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_125_content:
  string
  line `A witness who is unable to speak may give his`
  line `evidence in any other manner in which he can make it intelligible, as by writing or by signs; but such`
  line `writing must be written and the signs made in open Court and evidence so given shall be deemed to be`
  line `oral evidence:`
  line
  line `Provided that if the witness is unable to communicate verbally, the Court shall take the assistance of`
  line `an interpreter or a special educator in recording the statement, and such statement shall be videographed.`
obj_root_law_sections_125_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_126:
  sectionId (90893)
  sectionNo (126)
  orderNo 126
  title `Competency of husband and wife as witnesses in certain cases.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_126_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_126_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90893&sectionno=126&orderno=126&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_126_content:
  string
  line `(1) In all civil proceedings`
  line `the parties to the suit, and the husband or wife of any party to the suit, shall be competent witnesses.`
  line
  line `(2) In criminal proceedings against any person, the husband or wife of such person, respectively,`
  line `shall be a competent witness.`
obj_root_law_sections_126_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_127:
  sectionId (90894)
  sectionNo (127)
  orderNo 127
  title `Judges and Magistrates.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_127_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_127_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90894&sectionno=127&orderno=127&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_127_content:
  string
  line `No Judge or Magistrate shall, except upon the special order of some`
  line `Court to which he is subordinate, be compelled to answer any question as to his own conduct in Court as`
  line `such Judge or Magistrate, or as to anything which came to his knowledge in Court as such Judge or`
  line `Magistrate; but he may be examined as to other matters which occurred in his presence whilst he was so`
  line acting.
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A, on his trial before the Court of Session, says that a deposition was improperly taken by B, the`
  line `Magistrate. B cannot be compelled to answer questions as to this, except upon the special order of a`
  line `superior Court.`
  line
  line `(b) A is accused before the Court of Session of having given false evidence before B, a Magistrate. B`
  line `cannot be asked what A said, except upon the special order of the superior Court`
  line
  line `(c) A is accused before the Court of Session of attempting to murder a police officer whilst on his`
  line `trial before B, a Sessions Judge. B may be examined as to what occurred.`
obj_root_law_sections_127_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_128:
  sectionId (90895)
  sectionNo (128)
  orderNo 128
  title `Communications during marriage.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_128_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_128_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90895&sectionno=128&orderno=128&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_128_content:
  string
  line `No person who is or has been married, shall be`
  line `compelled to disclose any communication made to him during marriage by any person to whom he is or`
  line `has been married; nor shall he be permitted to disclose any such communication, unless the person who`
  line `made it, or his representative in interest, consents, except in suits between married persons, or`
  line `proceedings in which one married person is prosecuted for any crime committed against the other`
obj_root_law_sections_128_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_129:
  sectionId (90896)
  sectionNo (129)
  orderNo 129
  title `Evidence as to affairs of State.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_129_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_129_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90896&sectionno=129&orderno=129&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_129_content:
  string
  line `No one shall be permitted to give any evidence derived from`
  line `unpublished official records relating to any affairs of State, except with the permission of the officer at`
  line `the head of the department concerned, who shall give or withhold such permission as he thinks fit.`
obj_root_law_sections_129_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_130:
  sectionId (90897)
  sectionNo (130)
  orderNo 130
  title `Official communications.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_130_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_130_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90897&sectionno=130&orderno=130&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_130_content:
  string
  line `No public officer shall be compelled to disclose communications`
  line `made to him in official confidence, when he considers that the public interests would suffer by the`
  line disclosure.
obj_root_law_sections_130_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_131:
  sectionId (90898)
  sectionNo (131)
  orderNo 131
  title `Information as to commission of offences.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_131_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_131_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90898&sectionno=131&orderno=131&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_131_content:
  string
  line `No Magistrate or police officer shall be`
  line `compelled to say when he got any information as to the commission of any offence, and no revenue`
  line `officer shall be compelled to say when he got any information as to the commission of any offence`
  line `against the public revenue.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--"revenue officer" means any officer employed in or about the business of any branch`
  line `of the public revenue.`
obj_root_law_sections_131_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_132:
  sectionId (90899)
  sectionNo (132)
  orderNo 132
  title `Professional communications.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_132_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_132_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90899&sectionno=132&orderno=132&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_132_content:
  string
  line `(1) No advocate, shall at any time be permitted, unless with`
  line `his client’s express consent, to disclose any communication made to him in the course and for the`
  line `purpose of his service as such advocate, by or on behalf of his client, or to state the contents or condition`
  line `of any document with which he has become acquainted in the course and for the purpose of his`
  line `professional service, or to disclose any advice given by him to his client in the course and for the purpose`
  line `of such service:`
  line
  line `Provided that nothing in this section shall protect from disclosure of--`
  line
  line `(a) any such communication made in furtherance of any illegal purpose;`
  line
  line `(b) any fact observed by any advocate, in the course of his service as such, showing that any`
  line `crime or fraud has been committed since the commencement of his service.`
  line
  line `(2) It is immaterial whether the attention of such advocate referred to in the proviso to`
  line `sub-section (1), was or was not directed to such fact by or on behalf of his client.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--The obligation stated in this section continues after the professional service has`
  line ceased.
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A, a client, says to B, an advocate-- "I have committed forgery, and I wish you to defend me".`
  line `As the defence of a man known to be guilty is not a criminal purpose, this communication is protected`
  line `from disclosure.`
  line
  line `(b) A, a client, says to B, an advocate-- "I wish to obtain possession of property by the use of a`
  line `forged deed on which I request you to sue". This communication, being made in furtherance of a criminal`
  line `purpose, is not protected from disclosure.`
  line
  line `(c) A, being charged with embezzlement, retains B, an advocate, to defend him. In the course of the`
  line `proceedings, B observes that an entry has been made in A’s account book, charging A with the sum said`
  line `to have been embezzled, which entry was not in the book at the commencement of his professional`
  line `service. This being a fact observed by B in the course of his service, showing that a fraud has been`
  line `committed since the commencement of the proceedings, it is not protected from disclosure.`
  line
  line `(3) The provisions of this section shall apply to interpreters, and the clerks or employees of`
  line advocates.
obj_root_law_sections_132_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_133:
  sectionId (90900)
  sectionNo (133)
  orderNo 133
  title `Privilege not waived by volunteering evidence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_133_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_133_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90900&sectionno=133&orderno=133&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_133_content:
  string
  line `If any party to a suit gives evidence therein`
  line `at his own instance or otherwise, he shall not be deemed to have consented thereby to such disclosure as`
  line `is mentioned in section 132; and, if any party to a suit or proceeding calls any such advocate, as a`
  line `witness, he shall be deemed to have consented to such disclosure only if he questions such advocate, on`
  line `matters which, but for such question, he would not be at liberty to disclose.`
obj_root_law_sections_133_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_134:
  sectionId (90901)
  sectionNo (134)
  orderNo 134
  title `Confidential communication with legal advisers.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_134_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_134_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90901&sectionno=134&orderno=134&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_134_content:
  string
  line `No one shall be compelled to disclose to`
  line `the Court any confidential communication which has taken place between him and his legal adviser,`
  line `unless he offers himself as a witness, in which case he may be compelled to disclose any such`
  line `communications as may appear to the Court necessary to be known in order to explain any evidence`
  line `which he has given, but no others`
obj_root_law_sections_134_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_135:
  sectionId (90902)
  sectionNo (135)
  orderNo 135
  title `Production of title-deeds of witness not a party.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_135_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_135_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90902&sectionno=135&orderno=135&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_135_content:
  string
  line `No witness who is not a party to a suit shall`
  line `be compelled to produce his title-deeds to any property, or any document in virtue of which he holds any`
  line `property as pledgee or mortgagee or any document the production of which might tend to criminate him,`
  line `unless he has agreed in writing to produce them with the person seeking the production of such deeds or`
  line `some person through whom he claims`
obj_root_law_sections_135_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_136:
  sectionId (90949)
  sectionNo (136)
  orderNo 136
  title `Production of documents or electronic records which another person, having possession, could refuse to produce.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_136_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_136_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90949&sectionno=136&orderno=136&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_136_content:
  string
  line `No one shall be compelled to produce documents in his possession or electronic records under his control, which any other person would be entitled to refuse to produce if they`
  line `were in his possession or control, unless such last-mentioned person consents to their production.`
obj_root_law_sections_136_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_137:
  sectionId (90904)
  sectionNo (137)
  orderNo 137
  title `Witness not excused from answering on ground that answer will criminate.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_137_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_137_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90904&sectionno=137&orderno=137&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_137_content:
  string
  line `A witness`
  line `shall not be excused from answering any question as to any matter relevant to the matter in issue in any`
  line `suit or in any civil or criminal proceeding, upon the ground that the answer to such question will`
  line `criminate, or may tend directly or indirectly to criminate, such witness, or that it will expose, or tend`
  line `directly or indirectly to expose, such witness to a penalty or forfeiture of any kind:`
  line
  line `Provided that no such answer, which a witness shall be compelled to give, shall subject him to any`
  line `arrest or prosecution, or be proved against him in any criminal proceeding, except a prosecution forgiving`
  line `false evidence by such answer.`
obj_root_law_sections_137_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_138:
  sectionId (90905)
  sectionNo (138)
  orderNo 138
  title Accomplice.
  content obj_root_law_sections_138_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_138_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90905&sectionno=138&orderno=138&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_138_content:
  string
  line `An accomplice shall be a competent witness against an accused person; and a`
  line `conviction is not illegal if it proceeds upon the corroborated testimony of an accomplice.`
obj_root_law_sections_138_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_139:
  sectionId (90906)
  sectionNo (139)
  orderNo 139
  title `Number of witnesses.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_139_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_139_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90906&sectionno=139&orderno=139&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_139_content:
  string
  line `No particular number of witnesses shall in any case be required for the`
  line `proof of any fact.`
obj_root_law_sections_139_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_140:
  sectionId (90907)
  sectionNo (140)
  orderNo 140
  title `Order of production and examination of witnesses.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_140_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_140_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90907&sectionno=140&orderno=140&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_140_content:
  string
  line `The order in which witnesses are`
  line `produced and examined shall be regulated by the law and practice for the time being relating to civil and`
  line `criminal procedure respectively, and, in the absence of any such law, by the discretion of the Court.`
obj_root_law_sections_140_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_141:
  sectionId (90908)
  sectionNo (141)
  orderNo 141
  title `Judge to decide as to admissibility of evidence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_141_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_141_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90908&sectionno=141&orderno=141&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_141_content:
  string
  line `(1) When either party proposes to give`
  line `evidence of any fact, the Judge may ask the party proposing to give the evidence in what manner the`
  line `alleged fact, if proved, would be relevant; and the Judge shall admit the evidence if he thinks that the fact,`
  line `if proved, would be relevant, and not otherwise.`
  line
  line `(2) If the fact proposed to be proved is one of which evidence is admissible only upon proof of some`
  line `other fact, such last mentioned fact must be proved before evidence is given of the fact first mentioned,`
  line `unless the party undertakes to give proof of such fact, and the Court is satisfied with such undertaking.`
  line
  line `(3) If the relevancy of one alleged fact depends upon another alleged fact being first proved, the`
  line `Judge may, in his discretion, either permit evidence of the first fact to be given before the second fact is`
  line `proved, or require evidence to be given of the second fact before evidence is given of the first fact.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) It is proposed to prove a statement about a relevant fact by a person alleged to be dead, which`
  line `statement is relevant under section 26. The fact that the person is dead must be proved by the person`
  line `proposing to prove the statement, before evidence is given of the statement.`
  line
  line `(b) It is proposed to prove, by a copy, the contents of a document said to be lost. The fact that the`
  line `original is lost must be proved by the person proposing to produce the copy, before the copy is produced.`
  line
  line `(c) A is accused of receiving stolen property knowing it to have been stolen. It is proposed to prove`
  line `that he denied the possession of the property. The relevancy of the denial depends on the identity of the`
  line `property. The Court may, in its discretion, either require the property to be identified before the denial of`
  line `the possession is proved, or permit the denial of the possession to be proved before the property is`
  line identified.
  line
  line `(d) It is proposed to prove a fact A which is said to have been the cause or effect of a fact in issue.`
  line `There are several intermediate facts B, C and D which must be shown to exist before the fact A can be`
  line `regarded as the cause or effect of the fact in issue. The Court may either permit A to be proved before B,`
  line `C or D is proved, or may require proof of B, C and D before permitting proof of A.`
obj_root_law_sections_141_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_142:
  sectionId (90909)
  sectionNo (142)
  orderNo 142
  title `Examination of witnesses.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_142_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_142_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90909&sectionno=142&orderno=142&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_142_content:
  string
  line `(1) The examination of a witness by the party who calls him shall`
  line `be called his examination-in-chief.`
  line
  line `(2) The examination of a witness by the adverse party shall be called his cross-examination.`
  line
  line `(3) The examination of a witness, subsequent to the cross-examination, by the party who called him,`
  line `shall be called his re-examination.`
obj_root_law_sections_142_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_143:
  sectionId (90910)
  sectionNo (143)
  orderNo 143
  title `Order of examinations.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_143_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_143_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90910&sectionno=143&orderno=143&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_143_content:
  string
  line `(1) Witnesses shall be first examined-in-chief, then (if the adverse`
  line `party so desires) cross-examined, then (if the party calling him so desires) re-examined.`
  line
  line `(2) The examination-in-chief and cross-examination must relate to relevant facts, but the`
  line `cross-examination need not be confined to the facts to which the witness testified on his examination-inchief.`
  line
  line `(3) The re-examination shall be directed to the explanation of matters referred to in`
  line `cross-examination; and, if new matter is, by permission of the Court, introduced in re-examination, the`
  line `adverse party may further cross-examine upon that matter.`
obj_root_law_sections_143_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_144:
  sectionId (90911)
  sectionNo (144)
  orderNo 144
  title `Cross examination of person called to produce a document.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_144_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_144_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90911&sectionno=144&orderno=144&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_144_content:
  string
  line `A person summoned to`
  line `produce a document does not become a witness by the mere fact that he produces it, and cannot be`
  line `cross-examined unless and until he is called as a witness.`
obj_root_law_sections_144_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_145:
  sectionId (90912)
  sectionNo (145)
  orderNo 145
  title `Witnesses to character.`
  content `Witnesses to character may be cross-examined and re-examined.`
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_145_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90912&sectionno=145&orderno=145&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_145_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_146:
  sectionId (90913)
  sectionNo (146)
  orderNo 146
  title `Leading questions.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_146_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_146_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90913&sectionno=146&orderno=146&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_146_content:
  string
  line `(1) Any question suggesting the answer which the person putting it`
  line `wishes or expects to receive, is called a leading question.`
  line
  line `(2) Leading questions must not, if objected to by the adverse party, be asked in an`
  line `examination-in-chief, or in a re-examination, except with the permission of the Court`
  line
  line `(3) The Court shall permit leading questions as to matters which are introductory or undisputed, or`
  line `which have, in its opinion, been already sufficiently proved.`
  line
  line `(4) Leading questions may be asked in cross-examination`
obj_root_law_sections_146_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_147:
  sectionId (90914)
  sectionNo (147)
  orderNo 147
  title `Evidence as to matters in writing.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_147_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_147_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90914&sectionno=147&orderno=147&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_147_content:
  string
  line `Any witness may be asked, while under examination,`
  line `whether any contract, grant or other disposition of property, as to which he is giving evidence, was not`
  line `contained in a document, and if he says that it was, or if he is about to make any statement as to the`
  line `contents of any document, which, in the opinion of the Court, ought to be produced, the adverse party`
  line `may object to such evidence being given until such document is produced, or until facts have been proved`
  line `which entitle the party who called the witness to give secondary evidence of it.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--A witness may give oral evidence of statements made by other persons about the`
  line `contents of documents if such statements are in themselves relevant facts.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `The question is, whether A assaulted B. C deposes that he heard A say to D-- "B wrote a letter`
  line `accusing me of theft, and I will be revenged on him". This statement is relevant, as showing A's motive`
  line `for the assault, and evidence may be given of it, though no other evidence is given about the letter.`
obj_root_law_sections_147_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_148:
  sectionId (90915)
  sectionNo (148)
  orderNo 148
  title `Cross examination as to previous statements in writing.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_148_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_148_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90915&sectionno=148&orderno=148&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_148_content:
  string
  line `A witness may be cross-examined`
  line `as to previous statements made by him in writing or reduced into writing, and relevant to matters in`
  line `question, without such writing being shown to him, or being proved; but, if it is intended to contradict`
  line `him by the writing, his attention must, before the writing can be proved, be called to those parts of it`
  line `which are to be used for the purpose of contradicting him.`
obj_root_law_sections_148_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_149:
  sectionId (90916)
  sectionNo (149)
  orderNo 149
  title `Questions lawful in cross examination.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_149_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_149_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90916&sectionno=149&orderno=149&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_149_content:
  string
  line `When a witness is cross-examined, he may, in`
  line `addition to the questions hereinbefore referred to, be asked any questions which tend--`
  line
  line `(a) to test his veracity; or`
  line
  line `(b) to discover who he is and what is his position in life; or`
  line
  line `(c) to shake his credit, by injuring his character, although the answer to such questions might tend`
  line `directly or indirectly to criminate him, or might expose or tend directly or indirectly to expose him to`
  line `a penalty or forfeiture:`
  line
  line `Provided that in a prosecution for an offence under section 64, section 65, section 66,`
  line `section 67, section 68, section 69, section 70 or section 71 of the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023 or for`
  line `attempt to commit any such offence, where the question of consent is an issue, it shall not be permissible`
  line `to adduce evidence or to put questions in the cross-examination of the victim as to the general immoral`
  line `character, or previous sexual experience, of such victim with any person for proving such consent or the`
  line `quality of consent.`
obj_root_law_sections_149_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_150:
  sectionId (90917)
  sectionNo (150)
  orderNo 150
  title `When witness to be compelled to answer.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_150_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_150_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90917&sectionno=150&orderno=150&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_150_content:
  string
  line `If any such question relates to a matter relevant to`
  line `the suit or proceeding, the provisions of section 137 shall apply thereto.`
obj_root_law_sections_150_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_151:
  sectionId (90918)
  sectionNo (151)
  orderNo 151
  title `Court to decide when question shall be asked and when witness compelled to answer.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_151_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_151_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90918&sectionno=151&orderno=151&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_151_content:
  string
  line `(1) If any such question relates to a matter not relevant to the suit or proceeding, except in so`
  line `far as it affects the credit of the witness by injuring his character, the Court shall decide whether or not`
  line `the witness shall be compelled to answer it, and may, if it thinks fit, warn the witness that he is not`
  line `obliged to answer it.`
  line
  line `(2) In exercising its discretion, the Court shall have regard to the following considerations,`
  line `namely:--`
  line
  line `(a) such questions are proper if they are of such a nature that the truth of the imputation conveyed`
  line `by them would seriously affect the opinion of the Court as to the credibility of the witness on the`
  line `matter to which he testifies;`
  line
  line `(b) such questions are improper if the imputation which they convey relates to matters so remote`
  line `in time, or of such a character, that the truth of the imputation would not affect, or would affect in a`
  line `slight degree, the opinion of the Court as to the credibility of the witness on the matter to which he`
  line testifies;
  line
  line `(c) such questions are improper if there is a great disproportion between the importance of the`
  line `imputation made against the witness's character and the importance of his evidence;`
  line
  line `(d) the Court may, if it sees fit, draw, from the witness's refusal to answer, the inference that the`
  line `answer if given would be unfavourable.`
obj_root_law_sections_151_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_152:
  sectionId (90919)
  sectionNo (152)
  orderNo 152
  title `Question not to be asked without reasonable grounds.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_152_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_152_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90919&sectionno=152&orderno=152&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_152_content:
  string
  line `No such question as is referred to in`
  line `section 151 ought to be asked, unless the person asking it has reasonable grounds for thinking that the`
  line `imputation which it conveys is well-founded.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) An advocate is instructed by another advocate that an important witness is a dacoit. This is a`
  line `reasonable ground for asking the witness whether he is a dacoit.`
  line
  line `(b) An advocate is informed by a person in Court that an important witness is a dacoit. The`
  line `informant, on being questioned by the advocate, gives satisfactory reasons for his statement. This is a`
  line `reasonable ground for asking the witness whether he is a dacoit.`
  line
  line `(c) A witness, of whom nothing whatever is known, is asked at random whether he is a dacoit. There`
  line `are here no reasonable grounds for the question`
  line
  line `(d) A witness, of whom nothing whatever is known, being questioned as to his mode of life and`
  line `means of living, gives unsatisfactory answers. This may be a reasonable ground for asking him if he is a`
  line dacoit.
obj_root_law_sections_152_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_153:
  sectionId (90920)
  sectionNo (153)
  orderNo 153
  title `Procedure of Court in case of question being asked without reasonable grounds.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_153_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_153_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90920&sectionno=153&orderno=153&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_153_content:
  string
  line `If the Court is of opinion that any such question was asked without reasonable grounds, it`
  line `may, if it was asked by any advocate, report the circumstances of the case to the High Court or other`
  line `authority to which such advocate is subject in the exercise of his profession.`
obj_root_law_sections_153_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_154:
  sectionId (90921)
  sectionNo (154)
  orderNo 154
  title `Indecent and scandalous questions.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_154_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_154_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90921&sectionno=154&orderno=154&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_154_content:
  string
  line `The Court may forbid any questions or inquiries`
  line `which it regards as indecent or scandalous, although such questions or inquiries may have some bearing on the questions before the Court, unless they relate to facts in issue, or to matters necessary to be known`
  line `in order to determine whether or not the facts in issue existed.`
obj_root_law_sections_154_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_155:
  sectionId (90922)
  sectionNo (155)
  orderNo 155
  title `Questions intended to insult or annoy.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_155_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_155_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90922&sectionno=155&orderno=155&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_155_content:
  string
  line `The Court shall forbid any question which`
  line `appears to it to be intended to insult or annoy, or which, though proper in itself, appears to the Court`
  line `needlessly offensive in form.`
obj_root_law_sections_155_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_156:
  sectionId (90923)
  sectionNo (156)
  orderNo 156
  title `Exclusion of evidence to contradict answers to questions testing veracity.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_156_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_156_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90923&sectionno=156&orderno=156&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_156_content:
  string
  line `When a`
  line `witness has been asked and has answered any question which is relevant to the inquiry only in so far as it`
  line `tends to shake his credit by injuring his character, no evidence shall be given to contradict him; but, if he`
  line `answers falsely, he may afterwards be charged with giving false evidence.`
  line
  line `Exception 1.--If a witness is asked whether he has been previously convicted of any crime and`
  line `denies it, evidence may be given of his previous conviction.`
  line
  line `Exception 2.--If a witness is asked any question tending to impeach his impartiality, and answers it`
  line `by denying the facts suggested, he may be contradicted.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A claim against an underwriter is resisted on the ground of fraud. The claimant is asked whether,`
  line `in a former transaction, he had not made a fraudulent claim. He denies it. Evidence is offered to show that`
  line `he did make such a claim. The evidence is inadmissible`
  line
  line `(b) A witness is asked whether he was not dismissed from a situation for dishonesty. He denies it.`
  line `Evidence is offered to show that he was dismissed for dishonesty. The evidence is not admissible.`
  line
  line `(c) A affirms that on a certain day he saw B at Goa. A is asked whether he himself was not on that`
  line `day at Varanasi. He denies it. Evidence is offered to show that A was on that day at Varanasi. The`
  line `evidence is admissible, not as contradicting A on a fact which affects his credit, but as contradicting the`
  line `alleged fact that B was seen on the day in question in Goa. In each of these cases, the witness might, if his`
  line `denial was false, be charged with giving false evidence.`
  line
  line `(d) A is asked whether his family has not had a blood feud with the family of B against whom he`
  line `gives evidence. He denies it. He may be contradicted on the ground that the question tends to impeach his`
  line impartiality.
obj_root_law_sections_156_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_157:
  sectionId (90924)
  sectionNo (157)
  orderNo 157
  title `Question by party to his own witness.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_157_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_157_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90924&sectionno=157&orderno=157&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_157_content:
  string
  line `(1) The Court may, in its discretion, permit the`
  line `person who calls a witness to put any question to him which might be put in cross-examination by the`
  line `adverse party.`
  line
  line `(2) Nothing in this section shall disentitle the person so permitted under sub-section (1), to rely on`
  line `any part of the evidence of such witness.`
obj_root_law_sections_157_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_158:
  sectionId (90925)
  sectionNo (158)
  orderNo 158
  title `Impeaching credit of witness.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_158_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_158_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90925&sectionno=158&orderno=158&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_158_content:
  string
  line `The credit of a witness may be impeached in the following`
  line `ways by the adverse party, or, with the consent of the Court, by the party who calls him--`
  line
  line `(a) by the evidence of persons who testify that they, from their knowledge of the witness, believe`
  line `him to be unworthy of credit;`
  line
  line `(b) by proof that the witness has been bribed, or has accepted the offer of a bribe, or has received`
  line `any other corrupt inducement to give his evidence;`
  line
  line `(c) by proof of former statements inconsistent with any part of his evidence which is liable to be`
  line contradicted.
  line
  line `Explanation.--A witness declaring another witness to be unworthy of credit may not, upon his`
  line `examination-in-chief, give reasons for his belief, but he may be asked his reasons in cross-examination,`
  line `and the answers which he gives cannot be contradicted, though, if they are false, he may afterwards be`
  line `charged with giving false evidence.`
  line
  line Illustrations.
  line
  line `(a) A sues B for the price of goods sold and delivered to B. C says that he delivered the goods to B.`
  line `Evidence is offered to show that, on a previous occasion, he said that he had not delivered goods to B.`
  line `The evidence is admissible.`
  line
  line `(b) A is accused of the murder of B. C says that B, when dying, declared that A had given B the`
  line `wound of which he died. Evidence is offered to show that, on a previous occasion, C said that B, when`
  line `dying, did not declare that A had given B the wound of which he died. The evidence is admissible`
obj_root_law_sections_158_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_159:
  sectionId (90926)
  sectionNo (159)
  orderNo 159
  title `Questions tending to corroborate evidence of relevant fact, admissible.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_159_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_159_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90926&sectionno=159&orderno=159&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_159_content:
  string
  line `When a`
  line `witness whom it is intended to corroborate gives evidence of any relevant fact, he may be questioned as`
  line `to any other circumstances which he observed at or near to the time or place at which such relevant fact`
  line `occurred, if the Court is of opinion that such circumstances, if proved, would corroborate the testimony of`
  line `the witness as to the relevant fact which he testifies`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A, an accomplice, gives an account of a robbery in which he took part. He describes various incidents`
  line `unconnected with the robbery which occurred on his way to and from the place where it was committed.`
  line `Independent evidence of these facts may be given in order to corroborate his evidence as to the robbery`
  line itself.
obj_root_law_sections_159_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_160:
  sectionId (90927)
  sectionNo (160)
  orderNo 160
  title `Former statements of witness may be proved to corroborate later testimony as to same fact.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_160_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_160_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90927&sectionno=160&orderno=160&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_160_content:
  string
  line `In order to corroborate the testimony of a witness, any former statement made by such`
  line `witness relating to the same fact, at or about the time when the fact took place, or before any authority`
  line `legally competent to investigate the fact, may be proved.`
obj_root_law_sections_160_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_161:
  sectionId (90950)
  sectionNo (161)
  orderNo 161
  title `What matters may be proved in connection with proved statement relevant under section 26 or 27.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_161_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_161_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90950&sectionno=161&orderno=161&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_161_content:
  string
  line `Whenever any statement, relevant under section 26 or 27, is proved, all matters may`
  line `be proved either in order to contradict or to corroborate it, or in order to impeach or confirm the credit of`
  line `the person by whom it was made, which might have been proved if that person had been called as a`
  line `witness and had denied upon cross-examination the truth of the matter suggested.`
obj_root_law_sections_161_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_162:
  sectionId (90929)
  sectionNo (162)
  orderNo 162
  title `Refreshing memory.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_162_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_162_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90929&sectionno=162&orderno=162&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_162_content:
  string
  line `(1) A witness may, while under examination, refresh his memory by`
  line `referring to any writing made by himself at the time of the transaction concerning which he is questioned,`
  line `or so soon afterwards that the Court considers it likely that the transaction was at that time fresh in his`
  line `memory:`
  line
  line `Provided that the witness may also refer to any such writing made by any other person, and read by`
  line `the witness within the time aforesaid, if when he read it, he knew it to be correct.`
  line
  line `(2) Whenever a witness may refresh his memory by reference to any document, he may, with the`
  line `permission of the Court, refer to a copy of such document:`
  line
  line `Provided that the Court be satisfied that there is sufficient reason for the non-production of the`
  line `original:`
  line
  line `Provided further that an expert may refresh his memory by reference to professional treatises.`
obj_root_law_sections_162_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_163:
  sectionId (90930)
  sectionNo (163)
  orderNo 163
  title `Testimony to facts stated in document mentioned in section 162.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_163_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_163_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90930&sectionno=163&orderno=163&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_163_content:
  string
  line `A witness may also`
  line `testify to facts mentioned in any such document as is mentioned in section 162, although he has no`
  line `specific recollection of the facts themselves, if he is sure that the facts were correctly recorded in the`
  line document.
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A book-keeper may testify to facts recorded by him in books regularly kept in the course of business,`
  line `if he knows that the books were correctly kept, although he has forgotten the particular transactions`
  line entered.
obj_root_law_sections_163_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_164:
  sectionId (90931)
  sectionNo (164)
  orderNo 164
  title `Right of adverse party as to writing used to refresh memory.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_164_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_164_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90931&sectionno=164&orderno=164&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_164_content:
  string
  line `Any writing referred to`
  line `under the provisions of the two last preceding sections shall be produced and shown to the adverse party`
  line `if he requires it; such party may, if he pleases, cross-examine the witness thereupon.`
obj_root_law_sections_164_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_165:
  sectionId (90932)
  sectionNo (165)
  orderNo 165
  title `Production of documents.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_165_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_165_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90932&sectionno=165&orderno=165&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_165_content:
  string
  line `(1) A witness summoned to produce a document shall, if it is in`
  line `his possession or power, bring it to Court, notwithstanding any objection which there may be to its`
  line `production or to its admissibility:`
  line
  line `Provided that the validity of any such objection shall be decided on by the Court.`
  line
  line `(2) The Court, if it sees fit, may inspect the document, unless it refers to matters of State, or take`
  line `other evidence to enable it to determine on its admissibility`
  line
  line `(3) If for such a purpose it is necessary to cause any document to be translated, the Court may, if it`
  line `thinks fit, direct the translator to keep the contents secret, unless the document is to be given in evidence`
  line `and, if the interpreter disobeys such direction, he shall be held to have committed an offence`
  line `under section 198 of the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita, 2023:`
  line
  line `Provided that no Court shall require any communication between the Ministers and the President of`
  line `India to be produced before it.`
obj_root_law_sections_165_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_166:
  sectionId (90933)
  sectionNo (166)
  orderNo 166
  title `Giving, as evidence, of document called for and produced on notice.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_166_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_166_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90933&sectionno=166&orderno=166&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_166_content:
  string
  line `When a party`
  line `calls for a document which he has given the other party notice to produce, and such document is`
  line `produced and inspected by the party calling for its production, he is bound to give it as evidence if the`
  line `party producing it requires him to do so.`
obj_root_law_sections_166_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_167:
  sectionId (90934)
  sectionNo (167)
  orderNo 167
  title `Using, as evidence, of document production of which was refused on notice.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_167_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_167_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90934&sectionno=167&orderno=167&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_167_content:
  string
  line `When a party refuses to produce a document which he has had notice to produce, he cannot`
  line `afterwards use the document as evidence without the consent of the other party or the order of the Court.`
  line
  line Illustration.
  line
  line `A sues B on an agreement and gives B notice to produce it. At the trial, A calls for the document and`
  line `B refuses to produce it. A gives secondary evidence of its contents. B seeks to produce the document`
  line `itself to contradict the secondary evidence given by A, or in order to show that the agreement is not`
  line `stamped. He cannot do so.`
obj_root_law_sections_167_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_168:
  sectionId (90935)
  sectionNo (168)
  orderNo 168
  title `Judge's power to put questions or order production.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_168_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_168_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90935&sectionno=168&orderno=168&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_168_content:
  string
  line `The Judge may, in order to`
  line `discover or obtain proof of relevant facts, ask any question he considers necessary, in any form, at any`
  line `time, of any witness, or of the parties about any fact; and may order the production of any document or`
  line `thing; and neither the parties nor their representatives shall be entitled to make any objection to any such`
  line `question or order, nor, without the leave of the Court, to cross-examine any witness upon any answer`
  line `given in reply to any such question:`
  line
  line `Provided that the judgment must be based upon facts declared by this Adhiniyam to be relevant, and`
  line `duly proved:`
  line
  line `Provided further that this section shall not authorise any Judge to compel any witness to answer any`
  line `question, or to produce any document which such witness would be entitled to refuse to answer or`
  line `produce under sections 127 to 136, both inclusive, if the question were asked or the document were called`
  line `for by the adverse party; nor shall the Judge ask any question which it would be improper for any other`
  line `person to ask under section 151 or 152; nor shall he dispense with primary evidence of any document,`
  line `except in the cases hereinbefore excepted.`
obj_root_law_sections_168_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_169:
  sectionId (90936)
  sectionNo (169)
  orderNo 169
  title `No new trial for improper admission or rejection of evidence.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_169_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_169_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90936&sectionno=169&orderno=169&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_169_content:
  string
  line `The improper`
  line `admission or rejection of evidence shall not be ground of itself for a new trial or reversal of any decision`
  line `in any case, if it shall appear to the Court before which such objection is raised that, independently of the`
  line `evidence objected to and admitted, there was sufficient evidence to justify the decision, or that, if the`
  line `rejected evidence had been received, it ought not to have varied the decision.`
obj_root_law_sections_169_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_170:
  sectionId (90937)
  sectionNo (170)
  orderNo 170
  title `Repeal and savings.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_170_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_170_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654&sectionId=90937&sectionno=170&orderno=170&orgactid=AC_CEN_5_23_00049_2023-47_1719292804654
obj_root_law_sections_170_content:
  string
  line `(1) The Indian Evidence Act, 1872 (1 of 1872) is hereby repealed.`
  line
  line `(2) Notwithstanding such repeal, if, immediately before the date on which this Adhiniyam comes into`
  line `force, there is any application, trial, inquiry, investigation, proceeding or appeal pending, then, such`
  line `application, trial, inquiry, investigation, proceeding or appeal shall be dealt with under the provisions of`
  line `the Indian Evidence Act, 1872 (1 of 1872), as in force immediately before such commencement, as if this`
  line `Adhiniyam had not come into force.`
obj_root_law_sections_170_footnotes:
  string
  line
